# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: biological-process
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:biological-process/abiogenesis-p01] The study of abiogenesis aims to determine how pre-life chemical reactions gave rise to life under conditions strikingly different from those on Earth today.
[src:biological-process/abiogenesis-p01] It uses tools from biology and chemistry, attempting a synthesis of many sciences.
[src:biological-process/abiogenesis-p01] Life functions through the chemistry of carbon and water, and builds on four chemical families: lipids for cell membranes, carbohydrates such as sugars, amino acids for protein metabolism, and the nucleic acids DNA and RNA for heredity.
[src:biological-process/abiogenesis-p01] A theory of abiogenesis must explain the origins and interactions of these classes of molecules.
[src:biological-process/abiogenesis-p01] Many approaches investigate how self-replicating molecules came into existence.
[src:biological-process/abiogenesis-p01] Researchers think that life descends from an RNA world, although other self-replicating and self-catalyzing molecules may have preceded RNA.
[src:biological-process/abiogenesis-p01] Other approaches ("metabolism-first" hypotheses) focus on how catalysis on the early Earth might have provided the precursor molecules for self-replication.
[src:biological-process/abiogenesis-p01] The 1952 Miller–Urey experiment demonstrated that amino acids can be synthesized from inorganic compounds under conditions like early Earth's.
[src:biological-process/abiogenesis-p01] Subsequently, amino acids have been found in meteorites, comets, asteroids, and star-forming regions of space.
[src:biological-process/abiogenesis-p01] While the last universal common ancestor of all modern organisms (LUCA) existed millions of years after the origin of life, its study can guide research into early universal characteristics.
[src:biological-process/abiogenesis-p01] A genomics approach has sought to characterize LUCA by identifying the genes shared by Archaea and Bacteria, major branches of life.
[src:biological-process/abiogenesis-p01] It appears there are 60 proteins common to all life and 355 prokaryotic genes that trace to LUCA; their functions imply that LUCA was anaerobic with the Wood–Ljungdahl pathway, deriving energy by chemiosmosis, and used DNA, the genetic code, and ribosomes.
[src:biological-process/abiogenesis-p01] Earlier cells might have had a leaky membrane and been powered by a naturally occurring proton gradient near a deep-sea white smoker hydrothermal vent; or, life may have originated inside the continental crust or in water at Earth's surface.
[src:biological-process/abiogenesis-p01] Although Earth is the only place known to harbor life, astrobiologists assume that life exists and came into being by similar processes on other planets.
[src:biological-process/abiogenesis-p01] Geochemical and fossil evidence informs most studies.
[src:biological-process/abiogenesis-p01] The Earth was formed at 4.54 Gya, and the earliest evidence of life on Earth dates from 3.8 Gya from Western Australia.
[src:biological-process/abiogenesis-p01] Fossil micro-organisms may have lived in hydrothermal vent precipitates from Quebec, soon after ocean formation during the Hadean, so the process appears to have been relatively rapid in terms of geological time.
[src:biological-process/abiogenesis-p01] Life consists of reproduction with (heritable) variations.
[src:biological-process/abiogenesis-p01] That in turn implies a suite of cellular machinery including messenger RNA, transfer RNA, and ribosomes to translate the code into proteins.
[src:biological-process/abiogenesis-p01] Those proteins included enzymes to operate its anaerobic respiration via the Wood–Ljungdahl metabolic pathway, and a DNA polymerase to replicate its genetic material.
[src:biological-process/abiogenesis-p01] The challenge for origin of life researchers is to explain how such a complex and tightly interlinked system could develop by evolutionary steps, as at first sight all its parts are necessary to enable it to function.
[src:biological-process/abiogenesis-p01] For example, a cell, whether the LUCA or in a modern organism, copies its DNA with the DNA polymerase enzyme, which is itself produced by translating the DNA polymerase gene in the DNA.
[src:biological-process/abiogenesis-p01] Neither the enzyme nor the DNA can be produced without the other.
[src:biological-process/abiogenesis-p01] The evolutionary process could have started with molecular self-replication, self-assembly such as of cell membranes, and autocatalysis via RNA ribozymes in an RNA world environment.
[src:biological-process/abiogenesis-p01] The transition of non-life to life has not been observed experimentally.
[src:biological-process/abiogenesis-p01] Some scientists see both life and the origin of life as aspects of the same process.
[src:biological-process/abiogenesis-p01] The preconditions to the development of a living cell like the LUCA are known, though disputed in detail: a habitable world is formed with a supply of minerals and liquid water and sources of free energy inflows such as our Sun and geothermal heat.
[src:biological-process/abiogenesis-p01] Prebiotic synthesis creates a range of simple organic compounds, which are assembled into polymers such as proteins and RNA.
[src:biological-process/abiogenesis-p01] On the other side, the process after the LUCA is readily understood: biological evolution caused the development of a wide range of species with varied forms and biochemical capabilities.
[src:biological-process/abiogenesis-p01] However, the derivation of the LUCA from simple components is far from understood.
[src:biological-process/abiogenesis-p01] Although Earth remains the only place where life is known, the science of astrobiology seeks evidence of life on other planets.
[src:biological-process/abiogenesis-p01] The advent of such polymers was most likely a critical step in prebiotic chemical evolution.
[src:biological-process/abiogenesis-p01] Those polymers derived, in turn, from simple organic compounds such as nucleobases, amino acids, and sugars, likely formed by reactions in the environment.
[src:biological-process/abiogenesis-p01] A successful theory of the origin of life must explain how all these chemicals came into being.
[src:biological-process/abiogenesis-p01] One ancient view of the origin of life, from Aristotle until the 19th century, was of spontaneous generation.
[src:biological-process/abiogenesis-p01] This held that "lower" animals such as insects were generated by decaying organic substances, and that life arose by chance.
[src:biological-process/abiogenesis-p01] This was questioned from the 17th century, in works like Thomas Browne's *Pseudodoxia Epidemica*.
[src:biological-process/abiogenesis-p01] In 1665, Robert Hooke published the first drawings of a microorganism.
[src:biological-process/abiogenesis-p01] In 1676, Antonie van Leeuwenhoek drew and described microorganisms, probably protozoa and bacteria.
[src:biological-process/abiogenesis-p01] Van Leeuwenhoek disagreed with spontaneous generation, and by the 1680s convinced himself, using experiments ranging from sealed and open meat incubation and the close study of insect reproduction, that the theory was incorrect.
[src:biological-process/abiogenesis-p01] In 1668 Francesco Redi showed that no maggots appeared in meat when flies were prevented from laying eggs.
[src:biological-process/abiogenesis-p01] By the middle of the 19th century, spontaneous generation was considered disproven.
[src:biological-process/abiogenesis-p01] Dating back to Anaxagoras in the 5th century BC, panspermia is the idea that life originated elsewhere in the universe and came to Earth.
[src:biological-process/abiogenesis-p01] The modern version of panspermia holds that life may have been distributed to Earth by meteoroids, asteroids, comets or planetoids.
[src:biological-process/abiogenesis-p01] This shifts the origin of life to another heavenly body.
[src:biological-process/abiogenesis-p01] The advantage is that life is not required to have formed on each planet it occurs on, but in a more limited set of locations, and then spread about the galaxy to other star systems.
[src:biological-process/abiogenesis-p01] There is some interest in the possibility that life originated on Mars and later transferred to Earth.
[src:biological-process/abiogenesis-p01] The idea that life originated from non-living matter in slow stages appeared in Herbert Spencer's 1864–1867 book *Principles of Biology*, and in William Turner Thiselton-Dyer's 1879 paper "On spontaneous generation and evolution".
[src:biological-process/abiogenesis-p01] Haldane in 1929 proposed that the earliest cells slowly self-organized from a primordial soup, the Oparin–Haldane hypothesis.
[src:biological-process/abiogenesis-p01] Haldane suggested that the Earth's prebiotic oceans consisted of a "hot dilute soup" in which organic compounds could have formed.
[src:biological-process/abiogenesis-p01] Bernal showed that such mechanisms could form most of the necessary molecules for life from inorganic precursors.
[src:biological-process/abiogenesis-p01] In 1967, he suggested three "stages": the origin of biological monomers; the origin of biological polymers; and the evolution from molecules to cells.
[src:biological-process/abiogenesis-p01] In 1952, Stanley Miller and Harold Urey carried out a chemical experiment to demonstrate how organic molecules could have formed spontaneously from inorganic precursors under prebiotic conditions like those posited by the Oparin–Haldane hypothesis.
[src:biological-process/abiogenesis-p01] It passed an electric current through a highly reducing (lacking oxygen) mixture of gases—methane, ammonia, and hydrogen, with water vapor—to form organic monomers such as amino acids.
[src:biological-process/abiogenesis-p01] The addition of iron and carbonate minerals, present in early oceans, produces a diverse array of amino acids.
[src:biological-process/abiogenesis-p01] Later work has focused on two other potential reducing environments: outer space and deep-sea hydrothermal vents.
[src:biological-process/abiogenesis-p01] Soon after the Big Bang, roughly 14 Gya, the only chemical elements present in the universe were hydrogen, helium, and lithium, the three lightest atoms in the periodic table.
[src:biological-process/abiogenesis-p01] These elements gradually condensed into vast clouds of gas, which collapsed under gravity into rotating protostellar disks.
[src:biological-process/abiogenesis-p01] Gravitational accretion of material at the hot and dense centers of these disks formed the first stars by the fusion of hydrogen.
[src:biological-process/abiogenesis-p01] Early stars were massive and short-lived, producing all the heavier elements by stellar nucleosynthesis.
[src:biological-process/abiogenesis-p01] Such element formation proceeds to its most stable element Iron-56.
[src:biological-process/abiogenesis-p01] Heavier elements were formed during supernovas at the end of a star's lifecycle.
[src:biological-process/abiogenesis-p01] Carbon, currently the fourth most abundant element in the universe, was formed mainly in white dwarf stars.
[src:biological-process/abiogenesis-p01] As these stars reached the end of their lifecycles, they ejected heavier elements, including carbon and oxygen, throughout the universe.
[src:biological-process/abiogenesis-p01] These allowed for the formation of rocky planets.
[src:biological-process/abiogenesis-p01] According to the nebular hypothesis, the Solar System began to form 4.6 Gya with the gravitational collapse of part of a giant molecular cloud.
[src:biological-process/abiogenesis-p01] Most of the collapsing mass collected in the center, forming the Sun, while the rest flattened into a protoplanetary disk out of which the planets formed.
[src:biological-process/abiogenesis-p01] The age of the Earth is 4.54 Gya as found by radiometric dating of calcium-aluminium-rich inclusions in carbonaceous chrondrite meteorites, the oldest material in the Solar System.
[src:biological-process/abiogenesis-p01] Earth, during the Hadean eon (from its formation until 4.031 Gya,) was at first inhospitable to life.
[src:biological-process/abiogenesis-p01] During its formation, the Earth lost much of its initial mass, and so lacked the gravity to hold molecular hydrogen and the bulk of the original inert gases.
[src:biological-process/abiogenesis-p01] Soon after initial accretion of Earth at 4.48 Gya, its collision with Theia, a hypothesised impactor, is thought to have created the ejected debris that eventually formed the Moon.
[src:biological-process/abiogenesis-p01] This impact removed the Earth's primary atmosphere, leaving behind clouds of viscous silicates and carbon dioxide.
[src:biological-process/abiogenesis-p01] This unstable atmosphere was short-lived, soon condensing to form the bulk silicate Earth, leaving behind an atmosphere largely consisting of water vapor, nitrogen, and carbon dioxide, with smaller amounts of carbon monoxide, hydrogen, and sulfur compounds.
[src:biological-process/abiogenesis-p01] The solution of carbon dioxide in water is thought to have made the seas slightly acidic, with a pH of about 5.5.
[src:biological-process/abiogenesis-p01] Condensation to form liquid oceans is theorised to have occurred as early as the Moon-forming impact.
[src:biological-process/abiogenesis-p01] This scenario is supported by the dating of 4.404 Gya zircon crystals with high *δ*18O values from metamorphosed quartzite of Mount Narryer in Western Australia.
[src:biological-process/abiogenesis-p01] The Hadean atmosphere has been characterized as a "gigantic, productive outdoor chemical laboratory," similar to volcanic gases today which still support some abiotic chemistry.
[src:biological-process/abiogenesis-p01] Despite the likely increased volcanism from early plate tectonics, the Earth may have been a predominantly water world between 4.4 and 4.3 Gya.
[src:biological-process/abiogenesis-p01] It is debated whether crust was exposed above this ocean.
[src:biological-process/abiogenesis-p01] Immediately after the Moon-forming impact, Earth likely had little if any continental crust, a turbulent atmosphere, and a hydrosphere subject to intense ultraviolet light from a T Tauri stage Sun.
[src:biological-process/abiogenesis-p01] It was also affected by cosmic radiation, and continued asteroid and comet impacts.
[src:biological-process/abiogenesis-p01] The Late Heavy Bombardment hypothesis posits that a period of intense impact occurred at 4.1 to 3.8 Gya during the Hadean and early Archean eons.
[src:biological-process/abiogenesis-p01] Originally it was thought that the Late Heavy Bombardment was a single cataclysmic impact event occurring at 3.9 Gya; this would have had the potential to sterilize Earth by volatilizing liquid oceans and blocking sunlight needed for photosynthesis, delaying the earliest possible emergence of life.
[src:biological-process/abiogenesis-p01] More recent research questioned the intensity of the Late Heavy Bombardment and its potential for sterilisation.
[src:biological-process/abiogenesis-p01] If it was not one giant impact but a period of raised impact rate, it would have had much less destructive power.
[src:biological-process/abiogenesis-p01] The 3.9 Gya date arose from dating of Apollo mission sample returns collected mostly near the Imbrium Basin, biasing the age of recorded impacts.
[src:biological-process/abiogenesis-p01] Impact modelling of the lunar surface reveals that rather than a cataclysmic event at 3.9 Gya, multiple small-scale, short-lived periods of bombardment likely occurred.
[src:biological-process/abiogenesis-p01] Terrestrial data backs this idea by showing multiple periods of ejecta in the rock record both before and after the 3.9 Gya marker, suggesting that the early Earth was subject to continuous impacts with less impact on extinction.
[src:biological-process/abiogenesis-p01] If life evolved in the ocean at depths of more than ten meters, it would have been shielded both from late impacts and the then high levels of ultraviolet radiation from the sun.
[src:biological-process/abiogenesis-p01] The available energy is maximized at 100–150 °C, the temperatures at which hyperthermophilic bacteria and thermoacidophilic archaea live.
[src:biological-process/abiogenesis-p01] Based on evidence from the geologic record, life most likely emerged on Earth between 4.32 and 3.48 Gya.
[src:biological-process/abiogenesis-p01] In 2017, the earliest physical evidence of life was reported to consist of microbialites in the Nuvvuagittuq Greenstone Belt of Northern Quebec, in banded iron formation rocks at least 3.77 and possibly as old as 4.32 Gya.
[src:biological-process/abiogenesis-p01] The micro-organisms could have lived within hydrothermal vent precipitates, soon after the 4.4 Gya formation of oceans during the Hadean.
[src:biological-process/abiogenesis-p01] The microbes resemble modern hydrothermal vent bacteria, supporting the view that abiogenesis began in such an environment.
[src:biological-process/abiogenesis-p01] Later research disputed this interpretation of the data, stating that the observations may be better explained by abiotic processes in silica-rich waters, "chemical gardens," circulating hydrothermal fluids, or volcanic ejecta.
[src:biological-process/abiogenesis-p01] Biogenic graphite has been found in 3.7 Gya metasedimentary rocks from southwestern Greenland and in microbial mat fossils from 3.49 Gya cherts in the Pilbara region of Western Australia.
[src:biological-process/abiogenesis-p01] Evidence of early life in rocks from Akilia Island, near the Isua supracrustal belt in southwestern Greenland, dating to 3.7 Gya, have shown biogenic carbon isotopes.
[src:biological-process/abiogenesis-p01] In other parts of the Isua supracrustal belt, graphite inclusions trapped within garnet crystals are connected to the other elements of life: oxygen, nitrogen, and possibly phosphorus in the form of phosphate, providing further evidence for life 3.7 Gya.
[src:biological-process/abiogenesis-p01] In the Pilbara region of Western Australia, compelling evidence of early life was found in pyrite-bearing sandstone in a fossilized beach, with rounded tubular cells that oxidized sulfur by photosynthesis in the absence of oxygen.
[src:biological-process/abiogenesis-p01] Carbon isotope ratios on graphite inclusions from the Jack Hills zircons suggest that life could have existed on Earth from 4.1 Gya.
[src:biological-process/abiogenesis-p01] A 2024 study inferred LUCA's age as around 4.2 Gya (4.09–4.33 Gya) by analysing pre-LUCA gene duplicates, with calibration from fossil micro-organisms, much sooner after the origin of life than previously thought.
[src:biological-process/abiogenesis-p01] The Pilbara region of Western Australia contains the Dresser Formation with rocks 3.48 Gya, including layered structures called stromatolites.
[src:biological-process/abiogenesis-p01] Their modern counterparts are created by photosynthetic micro-organisms including cyanobacteria.
[src:biological-process/abiogenesis-p01] These lie within undeformed hydrothermal-sedimentary strata; their texture indicates a biogenic origin.
[src:biological-process/abiogenesis-p01] Parts of the Dresser formation preserve hot springs on land, but other regions seem to have been shallow seas.
[src:biological-process/abiogenesis-p01] A molecular clock analysis suggests the LUCA emerged prior to 3.9 Gya.
[src:biological-process/abiogenesis-p01] All chemical elements derive from stellar nucleosynthesis except for hydrogen and some helium and lithium.
[src:biological-process/abiogenesis-p01] Basic chemical ingredients of life – the carbon-hydrogen molecule (CH), the carbon-hydrogen positive ion (CH+) and the carbon ion (C+) – can be produced by ultraviolet light from stars.
[src:biological-process/abiogenesis-p01] Complex molecules, including organic molecules, form naturally both in space and on planets.
[src:biological-process/abiogenesis-p01] An organic compound is a chemical whose molecules contain carbon.
[src:biological-process/abiogenesis-p01] Carbon is abundant in the Sun, stars, comets, and in the atmospheres of most planets of the Solar System.
[src:biological-process/abiogenesis-p01] Organic compounds are relatively common in space, formed by "factories of complex molecular synthesis" which occur in molecular clouds and circumstellar envelopes, and chemically evolve after reactions are initiated mostly by ionizing radiation.
[src:biological-process/abiogenesis-p01] Purine and pyrimidine nucleobases including guanine, adenine, cytosine, uracil, and thymine, as well as sugars, have been found in meteorites.
[src:biological-process/abiogenesis-p01] These could have provided the materials for DNA and RNA to form on the early Earth.
[src:biological-process/abiogenesis-p01] The amino acid glycine was found in material ejected from comet Wild 2; it had earlier been detected in meteorites.
[src:biological-process/abiogenesis-p01] Comets are encrusted with dark material, thought to be a tar-like organic substance formed from simple carbon compounds under ionizing radiation.
[src:biological-process/abiogenesis-p01] A rain of material from comets could have brought such complex organic molecules to Earth.
[src:biological-process/abiogenesis-p01] During the Late Heavy Bombardment, meteorites may have delivered up to five million tons of organic prebiotic elements to Earth per year.
[src:biological-process/abiogenesis-p01] Currently 40,000 tons of cosmic dust falls to Earth each year.
[src:biological-process/abiogenesis-p01] Polycyclic aromatic hydrocarbons (PAH) are the most common and abundant polyatomic molecules in the observable universe, and are a major store of carbon.
[src:biological-process/abiogenesis-p01] They seem to have formed shortly after the Big Bang, and are associated with new stars and exoplanets.
[src:biological-process/abiogenesis-p01] They are a likely constituent of Earth's primordial sea.
[src:biological-process/abiogenesis-p01] PAHs have been detected in nebulae, and in the interstellar medium, in comets, and in meteorites.
[src:biological-process/abiogenesis-p01] A star, HH 46-IR, resembling the sun early in its life, is surrounded by a disk of material which contains molecules including cyanide compounds, hydrocarbons, and carbon monoxide.
[src:biological-process/abiogenesis-p01] PAHs in the interstellar medium can be transformed through hydrogenation, oxygenation, and hydroxylation to more complex organic compounds used in living cells.
[src:biological-process/abiogenesis-p01] Organic compounds introduced on Earth by interstellar dust particles can help to form complex molecules, thanks to their peculiar surface-catalytic activities.
[src:biological-process/abiogenesis-p01] The RNA component uracil and related molecules, including xanthine, in the Murchison meteorite were likely formed extraterrestrially, as suggested by studies of 12C/13C isotopic ratios.
[src:biological-process/abiogenesis-p01] NASA studies of meteorites suggest that all four DNA nucleobases (adenine, guanine and related organic molecules) have been formed in outer space.
[src:biological-process/abiogenesis-p01] The cosmic dust permeating the universe contains complex organics ("amorphous organic solids with a mixed aromatic–aliphatic structure") that could be created rapidly by stars.
[src:biological-process/abiogenesis-p01] Glycolaldehyde, a sugar molecule and RNA precursor, has been detected in regions of space including around protostars and on meteorites.
[src:biological-process/abiogenesis-p01] As early as the 1860s, experiments demonstrated that biologically relevant molecules can be produced from interaction of simple carbon sources with abundant inorganic catalysts.
[src:biological-process/abiogenesis-p01] The spontaneous formation of complex polymers from abiotically generated monomers under the conditions posited by the "soup" theory is not straightforward.
[src:biological-process/abiogenesis-p01] Besides the necessary basic organic monomers, compounds that would have prohibited the formation of polymers were also formed in high concentration during the Miller–Urey experiment and Joan Oró experiments.
[src:biological-process/abiogenesis-p01] Biology uses essentially 20 amino acids for its coded protein enzymes, representing a very small subset of the structurally possible products.
[src:biological-process/abiogenesis-p01] Since life tends to use whatever is available, an explanation is needed for why the set used is so small.
[src:biological-process/abiogenesis-p01] Formamide is attractive as a medium that potentially provided a source of amino acid derivatives from simple aldehyde and nitrile feedstocks.
[src:biological-process/abiogenesis-p01] Alexander Butlerov showed in 1861 that the formose reaction created sugars including tetroses, pentoses, and hexoses when formaldehyde is heated under basic conditions with divalent metal ions like calcium.
[src:biological-process/abiogenesis-p01] Breslow proposed that the reaction was autocatalytic in 1959.
[src:biological-process/abiogenesis-p01] Nucleobases, such as guanine and adenine, can be synthesized from simple carbon and nitrogen sources, such as hydrogen cyanide (HCN) and ammonia.
[src:biological-process/abiogenesis-p01] On early Earth, HCN was likely supplied via photochemical production in a transient, highly reducing atmosphere after major impacts.
[src:biological-process/abiogenesis-p01] Formamide, from the reaction of water and HCN, produces all four ribonucleotides when warmed with terrestrial minerals.
[src:biological-process/abiogenesis-p01] HCN can contribute to chemical processes such as the synthesis of the amino acid glycine.
[src:biological-process/abiogenesis-p01] DNA and RNA components including uracil, cytosine and thymine can be synthesized under outer space conditions, using starting chemicals such as pyrimidine from meteorites.
[src:biological-process/abiogenesis-p01] Pyrimidine may have formed in red giant stars, interstellar dust, or gas clouds, or on Earth via precursors such as cyanoacetylene following asteroid impacts.
[src:biological-process/abiogenesis-p01] All four RNA-bases may be synthesized from formamide in high-energy density events like extraterrestrial impacts.
[src:biological-process/abiogenesis-p01] Several ribonucleotides for RNA formation have been synthesized in a laboratory environment which replicates prebiotic conditions via autocatalytic formose reaction.
[src:biological-process/abiogenesis-p01] Other pathways for synthesizing bases from inorganic materials have been reported.
[src:biological-process/abiogenesis-p01] Freezing temperatures assist the synthesis of purines, by concentrating key precursors such as HCN.
[src:biological-process/abiogenesis-p01] However, while adenine and guanine require freezing conditions, cytosine and uracil may require boiling temperatures.
[src:biological-process/abiogenesis-p01] Seven amino acids and eleven types of nucleobases formed in ice when ammonia and cyanide were left in a freezer for 25 years.
[src:biological-process/abiogenesis-p01] S-triazines (alternative nucleobases), pyrimidines including cytosine and uracil, and adenine can be synthesized by subjecting a urea solution to freeze-thaw cycles under a reductive atmosphere with spark discharges.
[src:biological-process/abiogenesis-p01] These low-temperature reactions proceed rapidly due to eutectic freezing, which crowds impurities in microscopic pockets of liquid within the ice.
[src:biological-process/abiogenesis-p01] Prebiotic peptide synthesis could have occurred by several routes.
[src:biological-process/abiogenesis-p01] Some center on high temperature/concentration conditions in which condensation becomes energetically favorable, while others use plausible prebiotic condensing agents.
[src:biological-process/abiogenesis-p01] Experimental evidence for the formation of peptides in uniquely concentrated environments is bolstered by work suggesting that wet-dry cycles and the presence of specific salts can greatly increase spontaneous condensation of glycine into poly-glycine chains.
[src:biological-process/abiogenesis-p01] Other work suggests that while mineral surfaces, such as those of pyrite, calcite, and rutile catalyze peptide condensation, they also catalyze their hydrolysis.
[src:biological-process/abiogenesis-p01] The authors suggest that additional chemical activation or coupling would be necessary to produce peptides at sufficient concentrations.
[src:biological-process/abiogenesis-p01] Thus, mineral surface catalysis, while important, is not sufficient alone for peptide synthesis.
[src:biological-process/abiogenesis-p01] Many prebiotically plausible condensing/activating agents have been identified, including the following: cyanamide, dicyanamide, dicyandiamide, diaminomaleonitrile, urea, trimetaphosphate, NaCl, CuCl2, (Ni,Fe)S, CO, carbonyl sulfide (COS), carbon disulfide (CS2), SO2, and diammonium phosphate (DAP).
[src:biological-process/abiogenesis-p01] A 2024 experiment used a sapphire substrate with a web of thin cracks under a heat flow, mimicking deep-ocean vents, to concentrate prebiotically-relevant building blocks from a dilute mixture by up to three orders of magnitude.
[src:biological-process/abiogenesis-p01] This could help to create biopolymers such as peptides.
[src:biological-process/abiogenesis-p01] A similar role has been suggested for clays, though this speculation has not been supported through experimental evidence.
[src:biological-process/abiogenesis-p01] The prebiotic synthesis of peptides from simpler molecules such as CO, NH3 and C, skipping the step of amino acid formation, is also very efficient.
[src:biological-process/abiogenesis-p01] The largest unanswered question in evolution is how simple protocells first arose and differed in reproductive contribution to the following generation, thus initiating evolution.
[src:biological-process/abiogenesis-p01] The lipid world theory postulates that the first self-replicating object was lipid-like.
[src:biological-process/abiogenesis-p01] Phospholipids form lipid bilayers (as in cell membranes) in water while under agitation.
[src:biological-process/abiogenesis-p01] These molecules were not present on early Earth, but other membrane-forming amphiphilic long-chain molecules were.
[src:biological-process/abiogenesis-p01] These bodies may expand by insertion of additional lipids, and may spontaneously split into two offspring of similar size and composition.
[src:biological-process/abiogenesis-p01] Lipid bodies may have provided sheltering envelopes for information storage, allowing the evolution of information-storing polymers like RNA.
[src:biological-process/abiogenesis-p01] Only one or two types of vesicle-forming amphiphiles have been studied.
[src:biological-process/abiogenesis-p01] Such site/compound pairs are transmissible to the daughter vesicles, leading to the emergence of distinct lineages of vesicles, subject to natural selection.
[src:biological-process/abiogenesis-p01] A protocell is a self-organized, self-ordered, spherical collection of lipids proposed as a stepping-stone to life, that is capable of evolving.
[src:biological-process/abiogenesis-p01] Self-assembled vesicles are essential components of primitive cells.
[src:biological-process/abiogenesis-p01] The theory of classical irreversible thermodynamics treats self-assembly under a generalized chemical potential within the framework of dissipative systems.
[src:biological-process/abiogenesis-p01] The second law of thermodynamics requires that overall entropy increases, yet life is distinguished by its great degree of organization.
[src:biological-process/abiogenesis-p01] Therefore, a boundary is needed to separate ordered life processes from chaotic non-living matter.
[src:biological-process/abiogenesis-p01] A functional protocell, which must exhibit Darwinian evolution, has not yet been achieved in a laboratory setting.
[src:biological-process/abiogenesis-p01] Szostak suggest that elementary protocells can give rise to primitive forms of differential reproduction, competition, and energy storage.
[src:biological-process/abiogenesis-p01] Competition for membrane molecules would favor stabilized membranes, suggesting a selective advantage for cross-linked fatty acids and even modern phospholipids.
[src:biological-process/abiogenesis-p01] Such micro-encapsulation would allow for metabolism within the membrane and the exchange of small molecules, while retaining large biomolecules inside.
[src:biological-process/abiogenesis-p01] Such a membrane is needed for a cell to create its own electrochemical gradient.
[src:biological-process/abiogenesis-p01] Vesicles can undergo an evolutionary process under pressure cycling conditions.
[src:biological-process/abiogenesis-p01] Simulating the systemic environment in tectonic fault zones within the Earth's crust, pressure cycling forms vesicles periodically, as well as random peptide chains which are selected for ability to integrate into the vesicle membrane.
[src:biological-process/abiogenesis-p01] Further selection of vesicles for stability could lead to functional peptide structures, increasing vesicle survival rate.
[src:biological-process/abiogenesis-p01] Life requires a loss of entropy, or disorder, as molecules organize themselves into living matter.
[src:biological-process/abiogenesis-p01] At the same time, the emergence of life is associated with the formation of structures beyond a certain threshold of complexity.
[src:biological-process/abiogenesis-p01] Multiple sources of energy were available for chemical reactions on the early Earth.
[src:biological-process/abiogenesis-p01] Heat from geothermal processes is a standard energy source for chemistry.
[src:biological-process/abiogenesis-p01] Other examples include sunlight, lightning, atmospheric entries of micro-meteorites, and implosion of bubbles in sea and ocean waves.
[src:biological-process/abiogenesis-p01] This has been confirmed by experiments and simulations.
[src:biological-process/abiogenesis-p01] Unfavorable reactions can be driven by highly favorable ones, as in the case of iron-sulfur chemistry.
[src:biological-process/abiogenesis-p01] For example, this was probably important for carbon fixation.
[src:biological-process/abiogenesis-p01] Carbon fixation by reaction of CO2 with H2S via iron-sulfur chemistry is favorable, and occurs at neutral pH and 100 °C.
[src:biological-process/abiogenesis-p01] Iron-sulfur surfaces, which are abundant near hydrothermal vents, can drive the production of small amounts of amino acids and other biomolecules.
[src:biological-process/abiogenesis-p01] In 1961, Peter Mitchell proposed chemiosmosis as a cell's primary system of energy conversion.
[src:biological-process/abiogenesis-p01] The mechanism, now ubiquitous in living cells, powers energy conversion in micro-organisms and in the mitochondria of eukaryotes, making it a likely candidate for early life.
[src:biological-process/abiogenesis-p01] Mitochondria produce adenosine triphosphate (ATP), the energy currency of the cell used to drive cellular processes such as chemical syntheses.
[src:biological-process/abiogenesis-p01] The mechanism of ATP synthesis involves a closed membrane in which the ATP synthase enzyme is embedded.
[src:biological-process/abiogenesis-p01] The energy required to release strongly bound ATP has its origin in protons that move across the membrane.
[src:biological-process/abiogenesis-p01] In modern cells, those proton movements are caused by the pumping of ions across the membrane, maintaining an electrochemical gradient.
[src:biological-process/abiogenesis-p01] However, as yet, the hypothesis is untested.
[src:biological-process/abiogenesis-p01] The RNA world hypothesis describes an early Earth with self-replicating and catalytic RNA but no DNA or proteins.
[src:biological-process/abiogenesis-p01] It was proposed in 1962 by Alexander Rich; the term was coined by Walter Gilbert in 1986.
[src:biological-process/abiogenesis-p01] Many researchers concur that an RNA world must have preceded modern DNA-based life.
[src:biological-process/abiogenesis-p01] However, it may not have been the first to exist.
[src:biological-process/abiogenesis-p01] There may have been over 30 chemical events between pre-RNA world to near-LUCA, just involving RNA.
[src:biological-process/abiogenesis-p01] RNA is central to the translation process.
[src:biological-process/abiogenesis-p01] Small RNAs can catalyze all the chemical groups and information transfers required for life.
[src:biological-process/abiogenesis-p01] RNA both expresses and maintains genetic information in modern organisms; its components are easily synthesized under early Earth conditions.
[src:biological-process/abiogenesis-p01] The structure of the ribosome has been called the "smoking gun", with a central core of RNA and no amino acid side chains within 18 Å of the active site that catalyzes peptide bond formation.
[src:biological-process/abiogenesis-p01] RNA replicase can both code and catalyse further RNA replication, i.e. it is autocatalytic.
[src:biological-process/abiogenesis-p01] Some catalytic RNAs can link smaller RNA sequences together, enabling self-replication.
[src:biological-process/abiogenesis-p01] Natural selection would then favor the proliferation of such autocatalytic sets.
[src:biological-process/abiogenesis-p01] Self-assembly of RNA may occur spontaneously in hydrothermal vents.
[src:biological-process/abiogenesis-p01] A preliminary form of tRNA could have assembled into a replicator molecule.
[src:biological-process/abiogenesis-p01] When this began to replicate, it may have had all three mechanisms of Darwinian selection: heritability, variation, and differential reproduction.
[src:biological-process/abiogenesis-p01] Its fitness would have depended on its ability to adapt, determined by its nucleotide sequence, and resource availability.
[src:biological-process/abiogenesis-p01] Starting with the work of Carl Woese from 1977, genomics studies have placed the last universal common ancestor (LUCA) of all modern life-forms between Bacteria and a clade formed by Archaea and Eukaryota in the phylogenetic tree of life.
[src:biological-process/abiogenesis-p01] A minority of studies have placed the LUCA in Bacteria, proposing that Archaea and Eukaryota are evolutionarily derived from within Eubacteria; Thomas Cavalier-Smith suggested in 2006 that the phenotypically diverse bacterial phylum Chloroflexota contained the LUCA.
[src:biological-process/abiogenesis-p01] In 2016, a set of 355 genes likely present in the LUCA was identified.
[src:biological-process/abiogenesis-p01] A total of 6.1 million prokaryotic genes from Bacteria and Archaea were sequenced, identifying 355 protein clusters from among 286,514 protein clusters that were probably common to the LUCA.
[src:biological-process/abiogenesis-p01] The results suggest that the LUCA was anaerobic with a Wood–Ljungdahl (reductive Acetyl-CoA) pathway, nitrogen- and carbon-fixing, thermophilic.
[src:biological-process/abiogenesis-p01] Its cofactors suggest dependence upon an environment rich in hydrogen, carbon dioxide, iron, and transition metals.
[src:biological-process/abiogenesis-p01] Its genetic material was probably DNA, requiring the 4-nucleotide genetic code, messenger RNA, transfer RNA, and ribosomes to translate the code into proteins such as enzymes.
[src:biological-process/abiogenesis-p01] LUCA likely inhabited an anaerobic hydrothermal vent setting in a geochemically active environment.
[src:biological-process/abiogenesis-p01] It was evidently already a complex organism, and must have had precursors; it was not the first living thing.
[src:biological-process/abiogenesis-p01] The physiology of LUCA has been in dispute.
[src:biological-process/abiogenesis-p01] Previous research identified 60 proteins common to all life.
[src:biological-process/abiogenesis-p01] Metabolic reactions inferred in LUCA are the incomplete reverse Krebs cycle, gluconeogenesis, the pentose phosphate pathway, glycolysis, reductive amination, and transamination.
[src:biological-process/abiogenesis-p02] A variety of geologic and environmental settings have been proposed for an origin of life.
[src:biological-process/abiogenesis-p02] These theories are often in competition with one another as there are many views of prebiotic compound availability, geophysical setting, and early life characteristics.
[src:biological-process/abiogenesis-p02] The first organism on Earth likely differed from LUCA.
[src:biological-process/abiogenesis-p02] Between the first appearance of life and where all modern phylogenies began branching, an unknown amount of time passed, with unknown gene transfers, extinctions, and adaptation to environmental niches.
[src:biological-process/abiogenesis-p02] Modern phylogenies provide more genetic evidence about LUCA than about its precursors.
[src:biological-process/abiogenesis-p02] Early micro-fossils may have come from a hot world of gases such as methane, ammonia, carbon dioxide, and hydrogen sulfide, toxic to much current life.
[src:biological-process/abiogenesis-p02] Analysis of the tree of life places thermophilic and hyperthermophilic bacteria and archaea closest to the root, suggesting that life may have evolved in a hot environment.
[src:biological-process/abiogenesis-p02] The deep sea or alkaline hydrothermal vent theory posits that life began at submarine hydrothermal vents.
[src:biological-process/abiogenesis-p02] William Martin and Michael Russell have suggested that this could have been in metal-sulphide-walled compartments acting as precursors for cell walls.
[src:biological-process/abiogenesis-p02] These form where hydrogen-rich fluids emerge from below the sea floor, as a result of serpentinization of ultra-mafic olivine with seawater and a pH interface with carbon dioxide-rich ocean water.
[src:biological-process/abiogenesis-p02] The vents form a sustained chemical energy source derived from redox reactions, in which electron donors (molecular hydrogen) react with electron acceptors (carbon dioxide); see iron–sulfur world theory.
[src:biological-process/abiogenesis-p02] Russell demonstrated that alkaline vents create an abiogenic proton motive force chemiosmotic gradient, ideal for abiogenesis.
[src:biological-process/abiogenesis-p02] Their microscopic compartments "provide a natural means of concentrating organic molecules," composed of iron-sulfur minerals such as mackinawite, endowed these mineral cells with the catalytic properties envisaged by Günter Wächtershäuser.
[src:biological-process/abiogenesis-p02] Electrostatic force caused by electrical potential gradient—cations like protons H+ diffuse down the electrical potential, anions in the opposite direction.
[src:biological-process/abiogenesis-p02] These two gradients together can be expressed as an electrochemical gradient, providing energy for abiogenic synthesis.
[src:biological-process/abiogenesis-p02] The proton motive force measures the potential energy stored as proton and voltage gradients across a membrane (differences in proton concentration and electrical potential).
[src:biological-process/abiogenesis-p02] In 2016, Martin suggested that the LUCA "may have depended heavily on the geothermal energy of the vent to survive".
[src:biological-process/abiogenesis-p02] That same year, RNA was produced in synthetic alkaline hydrothermal chimneys simulating deep-sea vents.
[src:biological-process/abiogenesis-p02] Researchers were able to generate RNA oligomers of up to 4 units in length.
[src:biological-process/abiogenesis-p02] This RNA was synthesized using activated ribonucleotides.
[src:biological-process/abiogenesis-p02] Additionally, these RNA oligomers could only be synthesized under certain conditions.
[src:biological-process/abiogenesis-p02] Pores at deep sea hydrothermal vents are suggested to have been occupied by membrane-bound compartments which promoted biochemical reactions.
[src:biological-process/abiogenesis-p02] Metabolic intermediates in the Krebs cycle, gluconeogenesis, amino acid bio-synthetic pathways, glycolysis, the pentose phosphate pathway, and including sugars like ribose, and lipid precursors can occur non-enzymatically at conditions relevant to deep-sea alkaline hydrothermal vents.
[src:biological-process/abiogenesis-p02] If the deep marine hydrothermal setting was the site, then life could have arisen as early as 4.0–4.2 Gya.
[src:biological-process/abiogenesis-p02] If life evolved in the ocean at depths of more than ten meters, it would have been shielded both from impacts and the then high levels of solar ultraviolet radiation.
[src:biological-process/abiogenesis-p02] The available energy in hydrothermal vents is maximized at 100–150 °C, the temperatures at which hyperthermophilic bacteria and thermoacidophilic archaea live.
[src:biological-process/abiogenesis-p02] Hyperthermophily could have been a result of convergent evolution in bacteria and archaea; a mesophilic environment has been called more likely.
[src:biological-process/abiogenesis-p02] Production of prebiotic organic compounds at hydrothermal vents is estimated to be 108 kg/yr.
[src:biological-process/abiogenesis-p02] Key prebiotic compounds, such as methane are in far lower concentrations at vents than in a Miller-Urey Experiment environment.
[src:biological-process/abiogenesis-p02] Some organic compounds are now understood to have been formed by other geological processes and inherited by vents.
[src:biological-process/abiogenesis-p02] Methane, for example, more likely comes from leached fluid inclusions formed deeper in oceanic crust from magmatic carbon.
[src:biological-process/abiogenesis-p02] Vents do not concentrate prebiotic materials, due to strong dilution by seawater.
[src:biological-process/abiogenesis-p02] This open system cycles compounds through vent minerals, leaving little residence time to accumulate.
[src:biological-process/abiogenesis-p02] All modern cells rely on phosphates for nucleotide backbone and potassium for protein formation, making it likely that the first life forms shared these functions.
[src:biological-process/abiogenesis-p02] These elements were not available in high quantities in the Archaean oceans.
[src:biological-process/abiogenesis-p02] However, phosphate can be concentrated in lakes, as in the modern Last Chance Lake.
[src:biological-process/abiogenesis-p02] Submarine hydrothermal vents are not conducive to condensation reactions to polymerise macromolecules.
[src:biological-process/abiogenesis-p02] An older argument was that key polymers were encapsulated in vesicles after condensation, which supposedly would not happen in saltwater.
[src:biological-process/abiogenesis-p02] However, while salinity inhibits vesicle formation from low-diversity mixtures of fatty acids, vesicle formation from a broader, more realistic mix of fatty-acid and 1-alkanol species is more resilient.
[src:biological-process/abiogenesis-p02] No studies have been able to experimentally demonstrate synthesis of sugars, amino acids, nucleases, nucleosides, nucleotides, or membrane-forming fatty acids under plausible vent conditions.
[src:biological-process/abiogenesis-p02] Surface bodies of water provide environments that dry out and rewet.
[src:biological-process/abiogenesis-p02] Wet-dry cycles concentrate prebiotic compounds and enable condensation reactions to polymerise macromolecules.
[src:biological-process/abiogenesis-p02] Moreover, lakes and ponds receive detrital input from weathering of continental apatite-containing rocks, the most common source of phosphates.
[src:biological-process/abiogenesis-p02] The amount of exposed continental crust in the Hadean is unknown, but models of early ocean depths and rates of ocean island and continental crust growth make it plausible that there was exposed land.
[src:biological-process/abiogenesis-p02] Another line of evidence for a surface start to life is the requirement for Ultraviolet radiation (UV) for organism function.
[src:biological-process/abiogenesis-p02] UV is necessary for the formation of the U+C nucleotide base pair by partial hydrolysis and nucleobase loss.
[src:biological-process/abiogenesis-p02] Simultaneously, UV can be harmful and sterilising to life, especially for simple early lifeforms with little ability to repair radiation damage.
[src:biological-process/abiogenesis-p02] Radiation levels from a young Sun were likely greater, and, with no ozone layer, harmful shortwave UV rays would reach the surface of Earth.
[src:biological-process/abiogenesis-p02] For life to begin, a shielded environment with influx from UV-exposed sources is necessary to both benefit and protect from UV.
[src:biological-process/abiogenesis-p02] Shielding under ice, liquid water, mineral surfaces (e.g. clay) or regolith is possible in a range of surface water settings.
[src:biological-process/abiogenesis-p02] Most branching phylogenies are thermophilic or hyperthermophilic, making it possible that LUCA and preceding lifeforms were similarly thermophilic.
[src:biological-process/abiogenesis-p02] Hot springs are formed from the heating of groundwater by geothermal activity.
[src:biological-process/abiogenesis-p02] This intersection allows for influxes of material from deep penetrating waters and from surface runoff that transports eroded continental sediments.
[src:biological-process/abiogenesis-p02] Interconnected groundwater systems create a mechanism for distribution of life to wider area.
[src:biological-process/abiogenesis-p02] Mulkidjanian and co-authors argue that marine environments did not provide the ionic balance and composition universally found in cells, or the ions required by essential proteins and ribozymes, especially with respect to high K+/Na+ ratio, Mn2+, Zn2+ and phosphate concentrations.
[src:biological-process/abiogenesis-p02] They argue that the only environments that do this are hot springs similar to ones at Kamchatka.
[src:biological-process/abiogenesis-p02] The hypothesized pre-biotic environments are similar to hydrothermal vents, with additional components that help explain peculiarities of the LUCA.
[src:biological-process/abiogenesis-p02] A phylogenomic and geochemical analysis of proteins plausibly traced to the LUCA shows that the ionic composition of its intracellular fluid is identical to that of hot springs.
[src:biological-process/abiogenesis-p02] The LUCA likely was dependent upon synthesized organic matter for its growth.
[src:biological-process/abiogenesis-p02] Experiments show that RNA-like polymers can be synthesized in wet-dry cycling and UV light exposure.
[src:biological-process/abiogenesis-p02] These polymers were encapsulated in vesicles after condensation.
[src:biological-process/abiogenesis-p02] Potential sources of organics at hot springs might have been transported by interplanetary dust particles, extraterrestrial projectiles, or atmospheric or geochemical synthesis.
[src:biological-process/abiogenesis-p02] Hot springs could have been abundant in volcanic landmasses during the Hadean.
[src:biological-process/abiogenesis-p02] A mesophilic start in surface bodies of waters hypothesis has evolved from Darwin's concept of a 'warm little pond' and the Oparin-Haldane hypothesis.
[src:biological-process/abiogenesis-p02] Freshwater bodies under temperate climates can accumulate prebiotic materials while providing suitable environmental conditions conducive to simple life forms.
[src:biological-process/abiogenesis-p02] Atmospheric reconstructions from geochemical proxies and models suggest that sufficient greenhouse gases were present to maintain surface temperatures between 0–40 °C.
[src:biological-process/abiogenesis-p02] If so, the temperature was suitable for life to begin.
[src:biological-process/abiogenesis-p02] Evidence for mesophily from biomolecular studies includes Galtier's G+C nucleotide thermometer.
[src:biological-process/abiogenesis-p02] G+C are more abundant in thermophiles due to the added stability of an additional hydrogen bond not present between A+T nucleotides. rRNA sequencing of modern lifeforms shows that LUCA's reconstructed G+C content was likely representative of moderate temperatures.
[src:biological-process/abiogenesis-p02] The diversity of thermophiles today could be a product of convergent evolution and horizontal gene transfer rather than an inherited trait from LUCA.
[src:biological-process/abiogenesis-p02] The reverse gyrase topoisomerase is found exclusively in thermophiles and hyperthermophiles, as it allows for coiling of DNA.
[src:biological-process/abiogenesis-p02] This enzyme requires the complex molecule ATP to function.
[src:biological-process/abiogenesis-p02] If an origin of life is hypothesised to involve a simple organism that had not yet evolved a membrane, let alone ATP, this would make the existence of reverse gyrase improbable.
[src:biological-process/abiogenesis-p02] Moreover, phylogenetic studies show that reverse gyrase originated in archaea, and transferred to bacteria by horizontal gene transfer, implying it was not present in the LUCA.
[src:biological-process/abiogenesis-p02] Cold-start theories presuppose large ice-covered regions.
[src:biological-process/abiogenesis-p02] Stellar evolution models predict that the Sun's luminosity was ≈25% weaker than it is today.
[src:biological-process/abiogenesis-p02] Fuelner states that although this significant decrease in solar energy would have formed an icy planet, there is strong evidence for the presence of liquid water, possibly driven by a greenhouse effect.
[src:biological-process/abiogenesis-p02] This would mean an early Earth with both liquid oceans and icy poles.
[src:biological-process/abiogenesis-p02] Ice melts that form from ice sheets or glacier melts create freshwater pools, another niche capable of wet-dry cycles.
[src:biological-process/abiogenesis-p02] While surface pools would be exposed to intense UV radiation, bodies of water within and under ice would be shielded, while remaining connected to exposed areas through ice cracks.
[src:biological-process/abiogenesis-p02] Impact melting would allow freshwater and meteoritic input, creating prebiotic components.
[src:biological-process/abiogenesis-p02] Near-seawater levels of sodium chloride destabilize fatty acid membrane self-assembly, making freshwater settings appealing for early membranous life.
[src:biological-process/abiogenesis-p02] Icy environments would trade the faster reaction rates that occur in warm environments for increased stability and accumulation of larger polymers.
[src:biological-process/abiogenesis-p02] Experiments simulating Europa-like conditions of ≈20 °C have synthesised amino acids and adenine, showing that Miller-Urey type syntheses can occur at low temperatures.
[src:biological-process/abiogenesis-p02] In an RNA world, the ribozyme would have had even more functions than in a later DNA-RNA-protein-world.
[src:biological-process/abiogenesis-p02] For RNA to function, it must be able to fold, a process hindered by temperatures above 30 °C.
[src:biological-process/abiogenesis-p02] While RNA folding in psychrophilic organisms is slower, so is hydrolysis, so folding is more successful.
[src:biological-process/abiogenesis-p02] Shorter nucleotides would not suffer from higher temperatures.
[src:biological-process/abiogenesis-p02] The continental crust, with tectonic fault zones could present a stable and well-protected environment for long-term prebiotic evolution.
[src:biological-process/abiogenesis-p02] Inside these systems of cracks and cavities, water and carbon dioxide present the bulk solvents.
[src:biological-process/abiogenesis-p02] Their phase state could vary between liquid, gaseous and supercritical, depending on pressure and temperature.
[src:biological-process/abiogenesis-p02] When forming two separate phases, the system provides optimal conditions for phase transfer reactions.
[src:biological-process/abiogenesis-p02] Concurrently, the contents of the tectonic fault zones are supplied with inorganic educts (e.g. carbon monoxide, hydrogen, ammonia, hydrogen cyanide, nitrogen, and phosphate) and simple organic molecules (e.g. amino acids, long-chain amines, fatty acids, long-chain aldehydes).
[src:biological-process/abiogenesis-p02] Part of the tectonic fault zones is at a depth of around 1000 m.
[src:biological-process/abiogenesis-p02] For carbon dioxide, it provides temperature and pressure conditions near the phase transition point between the supercritical and the gaseous state.
[src:biological-process/abiogenesis-p02] This allows lipophilic organic molecules that dissolve well in supercritical CO2 to accumulate, leading to local precipitation.
[src:biological-process/abiogenesis-p02] Periodic pressure variations such as caused by geysers or tidal influences result in periodic phase transitions, keeping the local reaction environment in a constant non-equilibrium state.
[src:biological-process/abiogenesis-p02] In presence of amphiphilic compounds (such as the long chain amines and fatty acids), subsequent generations of vesicles are formed that are selected for their stability.
[src:biological-process/abiogenesis-p02] Homochirality is the uniformity of materials composed of chiral (non-mirror-symmetric) units.
[src:biological-process/abiogenesis-p02] Living organisms use molecules with the same chirality: with almost no exceptions, amino acids are left-handed while nucleotides and sugars are right-handed.
[src:biological-process/abiogenesis-p02] Chiral molecules can be synthesized, but in the absence of a chiral source or a chiral catalyst, they are formed in a 50/50 (racemic) mixture of both forms.
[src:biological-process/abiogenesis-p02] Non-racemic mixtures can arise from racemic materials by asymmetric physical laws such as the electroweak interaction, or in asymmetric environments, such as those in which molecules are exposed to circularly polarized light of a given handedness.
[src:biological-process/abiogenesis-p02] It has been hypothesized that the solar nebula was such an environment, exposed to circularly-polarized radiation from an external source before or during the epoch of planet formation.
[src:biological-process/abiogenesis-p02] This proposal is consistent with the finding that some amino acids delivered to Earth in meteorites exhibit a chiral asymmetry of the same sign as terrestrial life.
[src:biological-process/abiogenesis-p02] Once established, a chirality imbalance may influence subsequent chemical evolution.
[src:biological-process/abiogenesis-p02] A small bias in the population can be amplified by asymmetric autocatalysis, as in the Soai reaction, where a chiral molecule catalyzes its own production.
[src:biological-process/adaptation] In biology, **adaptation** has three related meanings.
[src:biological-process/adaptation] Firstly, it is the dynamic evolutionary process of natural selection that fits organisms to their environment, enhancing their evolutionary fitness.
[src:biological-process/adaptation] Secondly, it is a state reached by the population during that process.
[src:biological-process/adaptation] Thirdly, it is a phenotypic trait or **adaptive trait**, with a functional role in each individual organism, that is maintained and has evolved through natural selection.
[src:biological-process/adaptation] Historically, adaptation has been described from the time of the ancient Greek philosophers such as Empedocles and Aristotle.
[src:biological-process/adaptation] In 18th and 19th-century natural theology, adaptation was taken as evidence for the existence of a deity.
[src:biological-process/adaptation] Charles Darwin and Alfred Russel Wallace proposed instead that it was explained by natural selection.
[src:biological-process/adaptation] Adaptation is related to biological fitness, which governs the rate of evolution as measured by changes in allele frequencies.
[src:biological-process/adaptation] Often, two or more species co-adapt and co-evolve as they develop adaptations that interlock with those of the other species, such as with flowering plants and pollinating insects.
[src:biological-process/adaptation] In mimicry, species evolve to resemble other species; in mimicry this is a mutually beneficial co-evolution as each of a group of strongly defended species (such as wasps able to sting) come to advertise their defences in the same way.
[src:biological-process/adaptation] Features evolved for one purpose may be co-opted for a different one, as when the insulating feathers of dinosaurs were co-opted for bird flight.
[src:biological-process/adaptation] Adaptation is a major topic in the philosophy of biology, as it concerns function and purpose (teleology).
[src:biological-process/adaptation] Some biologists try to avoid terms which imply purpose in adaptation, not least because they suggest a deity's intentions, but others note that adaptation is necessarily purposeful.
[src:biological-process/adaptation] Adaptation is an observable fact of life accepted by philosophers and natural historians from ancient times, independently of their views on evolution, but their explanations differed.
[src:biological-process/adaptation] Empedocles did not believe that adaptation required a final cause (a purpose), but thought that it "came about naturally, since such things survived." Aristotle did believe in final causes, but assumed that species were fixed.
[src:biological-process/adaptation] In natural theology, adaptation was interpreted as the work of a deity and as evidence for the existence of God.
[src:biological-process/adaptation] William Paley believed that organisms were perfectly adapted to the lives they led, an argument that shadowed Gottfried Wilhelm Leibniz, who had argued that God had brought about "the best of all possible worlds." Voltaire's satire Dr.
[src:biological-process/adaptation] Pangloss is a parody of this optimistic idea, and David Hume also argued against design.
[src:biological-process/adaptation] Charles Darwin broke with the tradition by emphasising the flaws and limitations which occurred in the animal and plant worlds.
[src:biological-process/adaptation] Jean-Baptiste Lamarck proposed a tendency for organisms to become more complex, moving up a ladder of progress, plus "the influence of circumstances", usually expressed as *use and disuse*.
[src:biological-process/adaptation] This second, subsidiary element of his theory is what is now called Lamarckism, a proto-evolutionary hypothesis of the inheritance of acquired characteristics, intended to explain adaptations by natural means.
[src:biological-process/adaptation] Other natural historians, such as Buffon, accepted adaptation, and some also accepted evolution, without voicing their opinions as to the mechanism.
[src:biological-process/adaptation] This illustrates the real merit of Darwin and Alfred Russel Wallace, and secondary figures such as Henry Walter Bates, for putting forward a mechanism whose significance had only been glimpsed previously.
[src:biological-process/adaptation] A century later, experimental field studies and breeding experiments by people such as E.
[src:biological-process/adaptation] Ford and Theodosius Dobzhansky produced evidence that natural selection was not only the 'engine' behind adaptation, but was a much stronger force than had previously been thought.
[src:biological-process/adaptation] Adaptation is primarily a process rather than a physical form or part of a body.
[src:biological-process/adaptation] An internal parasite (such as a liver fluke) can illustrate the distinction: such a parasite may have a very simple bodily structure, but nevertheless the organism is highly adapted to its specific environment.
[src:biological-process/adaptation] From this we see that adaptation is not just a matter of visible traits: in such parasites critical adaptations take place in the life cycle, which is often quite complex.
[src:biological-process/adaptation] However, as a practical term, "adaptation" often refers to a *product*: those features of a species which result from the process.
[src:biological-process/adaptation] Many aspects of an animal or plant can be correctly called adaptations, though there are always some features whose function remains in doubt.
[src:biological-process/adaptation] By using the term *adaptation* for the evolutionary *process*, and *adaptive trait* for the bodily part or function (the product), one may distinguish the two different senses of the word.
[src:biological-process/adaptation] Adaptation is one of the two main processes that explain the observed diversity of species, such as the different species of Darwin's finches.
[src:biological-process/adaptation] The other process is speciation, in which new species arise, typically through reproductive isolation.
[src:biological-process/adaptation] An example widely used today to study the interplay of adaptation and speciation is the evolution of cichlid fish in African lakes, where the question of reproductive isolation is complex.
[src:biological-process/adaptation] Adaptation is not always a simple matter where the ideal phenotype evolves for a given environment.
[src:biological-process/adaptation] An organism must be viable at all stages of its development and at all stages of its evolution.
[src:biological-process/adaptation] This places *constraints* on the evolution of development, behaviour, and structure of organisms.
[src:biological-process/adaptation] The main constraint, over which there has been much debate, is the requirement that each genetic and phenotypic change during evolution should be relatively small, because developmental systems are so complex and interlinked.
[src:biological-process/adaptation] However, it is not clear what "relatively small" should mean, for example polyploidy in plants is a reasonably common large genetic change.
[src:biological-process/adaptation] The origin of eukaryotic endosymbiosis is a more dramatic example.
[src:biological-process/adaptation] All adaptations help organisms survive in their ecological niches.
[src:biological-process/adaptation] The adaptive traits may be structural, behavioural or physiological.
[src:biological-process/adaptation] Structural adaptations are physical features of an organism, such as shape, body covering, armament, and internal organization.
[src:biological-process/adaptation] Behavioural adaptations are inherited systems of behaviour, whether inherited in detail as instincts, or as a neuropsychological capacity for learning.
[src:biological-process/adaptation] Examples include searching for food, mating, and vocalizations.
[src:biological-process/adaptation] Physiological adaptations permit the organism to perform special functions such as making venom, secreting slime, and phototropism, but also involve more general functions such as growth and development, temperature regulation, ionic balance and other aspects of homeostasis.
[src:biological-process/adaptation] Adaptation affects all aspects of the life of an organism.
[src:biological-process/adaptation] is the state of being adapted: the degree to which an organism is able to live and reproduce in a given set of habitats.
[src:biological-process/adaptation] is an aspect of the developmental pattern of the organism which enables or enhances the probability of that organism surviving and reproducing.
[src:biological-process/adaptation] Adaptation differs from flexibility, acclimatization, and learning, all of which are changes during life which are not inherited.
[src:biological-process/adaptation] Flexibility deals with the relative capacity of an organism to maintain itself in different habitats: its degree of specialization.
[src:biological-process/adaptation] Acclimatization describes automatic physiological adjustments during life; learning means alteration in behavioural performance during life.
[src:biological-process/adaptation] Flexibility stems from phenotypic plasticity, the ability of an organism with a given genotype (genetic type) to change its phenotype (observable characteristics) in response to changes in its habitat, or to move to a different habitat.
[src:biological-process/adaptation] The degree of flexibility is inherited, and varies between individuals.
[src:biological-process/adaptation] A highly specialized animal or plant lives only in a well-defined habitat, eats a specific type of food, and cannot survive if its needs are not met.
[src:biological-process/adaptation] Many herbivores are like this; extreme examples are koalas which depend on *Eucalyptus*, and giant pandas which require bamboo.
[src:biological-process/adaptation] A generalist, on the other hand, eats a range of food, and can survive in many different conditions.
[src:biological-process/adaptation] Examples are humans, rats, crabs and many carnivores.
[src:biological-process/adaptation] The *tendency* to behave in a specialized or exploratory manner is inherited—it is an adaptation.
[src:biological-process/adaptation] Rather different is developmental flexibility: "An animal or plant is developmentally flexible if when it is raised in or transferred to new conditions, it changes in structure so that it is better fitted to survive in the new environment," writes the evolutionary biologist John Maynard Smith.
[src:biological-process/adaptation] If humans move to a higher altitude, respiration and physical exertion become a problem, but after spending time in high altitude conditions they acclimatize to the reduced partial pressure of oxygen, such as by producing more red blood cells.
[src:biological-process/adaptation] The ability to acclimatize is an adaptation, but the acclimatization itself is not.
[src:biological-process/adaptation] The reproductive rate declines, but deaths from some tropical diseases also go down.
[src:biological-process/adaptation] Over a longer period of time, some people are better able to reproduce at high altitudes than others.
[src:biological-process/adaptation] They contribute more heavily to later generations, and gradually by natural selection the whole population becomes adapted to the new conditions.
[src:biological-process/adaptation] This has demonstrably occurred, as the observed performance of long-term communities at higher altitude is significantly better than the performance of new arrivals, even when the new arrivals have had time to acclimatize.
[src:biological-process/adaptation] There is a relationship between adaptedness and the concept of fitness used in population genetics.
[src:biological-process/adaptation] Differences in fitness between genotypes predict the rate of evolution by natural selection.
[src:biological-process/adaptation] Natural selection changes the relative frequencies of alternative phenotypes, insofar as they are heritable.
[src:biological-process/adaptation] However, a phenotype with high adaptedness may not have high fitness.
[src:biological-process/adaptation] Dobzhansky mentioned the example of the Californian redwood, which is highly adapted, but a relict species in danger of extinction.
[src:biological-process/adaptation] Elliott Sober commented that adaptation was a retrospective concept since it implied something about the history of a trait, whereas fitness predicts a trait's future.
[src:biological-process/adaptation] The absolute contribution to the next generation by a genotype or a class of genotypes.
[src:biological-process/adaptation] when applied to the population as a whole.
[src:biological-process/adaptation] The extent to which a phenotype fits its local ecological niche.
[src:biological-process/adaptation] Sewall Wright proposed that populations occupy *adaptive peaks* on a fitness landscape.
[src:biological-process/adaptation] To evolve to another, higher peak, a population would first have to pass through a valley of maladaptive intermediate stages, and might be "trapped" on a peak that is not optimally adapted.
[src:biological-process/adaptation] Before Darwin, adaptation was seen as a fixed relationship between an organism and its habitat.
[src:biological-process/adaptation] It was not appreciated that as the climate changed, so did the habitat; and as the habitat changed, so did the biota.
[src:biological-process/adaptation] Also, habitats are subject to changes in their biota: for example, invasions of species from other areas.
[src:biological-process/adaptation] The relative numbers of species in a given habitat are always changing.
[src:biological-process/adaptation] Change is the rule, though much depends on the speed and degree of the change.
[src:biological-process/adaptation] When the habitat changes, three main things may happen to a resident population: habitat tracking, genetic change or extinction.
[src:biological-process/adaptation] In fact, all three things may occur in sequence.
[src:biological-process/adaptation] Of these three effects only genetic change brings about adaptation.
[src:biological-process/adaptation] When a habitat changes, the resident population typically moves to more suitable places; this is the typical response of flying insects or oceanic organisms, which have wide (though not unlimited) opportunity for movement.
[src:biological-process/adaptation] This common response is called *habitat tracking*.
[src:biological-process/adaptation] It is one explanation put forward for the periods of apparent stasis in the fossil record (the punctuated equilibrium theory).
[src:biological-process/adaptation] Without mutation, the ultimate source of all genetic variation, there would be no genetic changes and no subsequent adaptation through evolution by natural selection.
[src:biological-process/adaptation] Genetic change occurs in a population when mutation increases or decreases in its initial frequency followed by random genetic drift, migration, recombination or natural selection act on this genetic variation.
[src:biological-process/adaptation] One example is that the first pathways of enzyme-based metabolism at the very origin of life on Earth may have been co-opted components of the already-existing purine nucleotide metabolism, a metabolic pathway that evolved in an ancient RNA world.
[src:biological-process/adaptation] The co-option requires new mutations and through natural selection, the population then adapts genetically to its present circumstances.
[src:biological-process/adaptation] Genetic changes may result in entirely new or gradual change to visible structures, or they may adjust physiological activity in a way that suits the habitat.
[src:biological-process/adaptation] The varying shapes of the beaks of Darwin's finches, for example, are driven by adaptive mutations in the ALX1 gene.
[src:biological-process/adaptation] The coat color of different wild mouse species matches their environments, whether black lava or light sand, owing to adaptive mutations in the melanocortin 1 receptor and other melanin pathway genes.
[src:biological-process/adaptation] Physiological resistance to the heart poisons (cardiac glycosides) that monarch butterflies store in their bodies to protect themselves from predators are driven by adaptive mutations in the target of the poison, the sodium pump, resulting in target site insensitivity.
[src:biological-process/adaptation] These same adaptive mutations and similar changes at the same amino acid sites were found to evolve in a parallel manner in distantly related insects that feed on the same plants, and even in a bird that feeds on monarchs through convergent evolution, a hallmark of adaptation.
[src:biological-process/adaptation] Convergence at the gene-level across distantly related species can arise because of evolutionary constraint.
[src:biological-process/adaptation] Habitats and biota do frequently change over time and space.
[src:biological-process/adaptation] Therefore, it follows that the process of adaptation is never fully complete.
[src:biological-process/adaptation] Over time, it may happen that the environment changes little, and the species comes to fit its surroundings better and better, resulting in stabilizing selection.
[src:biological-process/adaptation] On the other hand, it may happen that changes in the environment occur suddenly, and then the species becomes less and less well adapted.
[src:biological-process/adaptation] The only way for it to climb back up that fitness peak is via the introduction of new genetic variation for natural selection to act upon.
[src:biological-process/adaptation] Seen like this, adaptation is a genetic *tracking process*, which goes on all the time to some extent, but especially when the population cannot or does not move to another, less hostile area.
[src:biological-process/adaptation] Given enough genetic change, as well as specific demographic conditions, an adaptation may be enough to bring a population back from the brink of extinction in a process called evolutionary rescue.
[src:biological-process/adaptation] Adaptation does affect, to some extent, every species in a particular ecosystem.
[src:biological-process/adaptation] Leigh Van Valen thought that even in a stable environment, because of antagonistic species interactions and limited resources, a species must constantly had to adapt to maintain its relative standing.
[src:biological-process/adaptation] This became known as the Red Queen hypothesis, as seen in host-parasite interactions.
[src:biological-process/adaptation] Existing genetic variation and mutation were the traditional sources of material on which natural selection could act.
[src:biological-process/adaptation] In addition, horizontal gene transfer is possible between organisms in different species, using mechanisms as varied as gene cassettes, plasmids, transposons and viruses such as bacteriophages.
[src:biological-process/adaptation] In coevolution, where the existence of one species is tightly bound up with the life of another species, new or 'improved' adaptations which occur in one species are often followed by the appearance and spread of corresponding features in the other species.
[src:biological-process/adaptation] In other words, each species triggers reciprocal natural selection in the other.
[src:biological-process/adaptation] These co-adaptational relationships are intrinsically dynamic, and may continue on a trajectory for millions of years, as has occurred in the relationship between flowering plants and pollinating insects.
[src:biological-process/adaptation] Bates' work on Amazonian butterflies led him to develop the first scientific account of mimicry, especially the kind of mimicry which bears his name: Batesian mimicry.
[src:biological-process/adaptation] This is the mimicry by a palatable species of an unpalatable or noxious species (the model), gaining a selective advantage as predators avoid the model and therefore also the mimic.
[src:biological-process/adaptation] Mimicry is thus an anti-predator adaptation.
[src:biological-process/adaptation] A common example seen in temperate gardens is the hoverfly (Syrphidae), many of which—though bearing no sting—mimic the warning coloration of aculeate Hymenoptera (wasps and bees).
[src:biological-process/adaptation] Such mimicry does not need to be perfect to improve the survival of the palatable species.
[src:biological-process/adaptation] Bates, Wallace and Fritz Müller believed that Batesian and Müllerian mimicry provided evidence for the action of natural selection, a view which is now standard amongst biologists.
[src:biological-process/adaptation] All adaptations have a downside: horse legs are great for running on grass, but they cannot scratch their backs; mammals' hair helps temperature, but offers a niche for ectoparasites; the only flying penguins do is under water.
[src:biological-process/adaptation] Adaptations serving different functions may be mutually destructive.
[src:biological-process/adaptation] Compromise and makeshift occur widely, not perfection.
[src:biological-process/adaptation] Selection pressures pull in different directions, and the adaptation that results is some kind of compromise.
[src:biological-process/adaptation] Consider the antlers of the Irish elk, (often supposed to be far too large; in deer antler size has an allometric relationship to body size).
[src:biological-process/adaptation] Antlers serve positively for defence against predators, and to score victories in the annual rut.
[src:biological-process/adaptation] But they are costly in terms of resources.
[src:biological-process/adaptation] Their size during the last glacial period presumably depended on the relative gain and loss of reproductive capacity in the population of elks during that time.
[src:biological-process/adaptation] As another example, camouflage to avoid detection is destroyed when vivid coloration is displayed at mating time.
[src:biological-process/adaptation] Here the risk to life is counterbalanced by the necessity for reproduction.
[src:biological-process/adaptation] Stream-dwelling salamanders, such as Caucasian salamander or Gold-striped salamander have very slender, long bodies, perfectly adapted to life at the banks of fast small rivers and mountain brooks.
[src:biological-process/adaptation] Elongated body protects their larvae from being washed out by current.
[src:biological-process/adaptation] However, elongated body increases risk of desiccation and decreases dispersal ability of the salamanders; it also negatively affects their fecundity.
[src:biological-process/adaptation] As a result, fire salamander, less perfectly adapted to the mountain brook habitats, is in general more successful, have a higher fecundity and broader geographic range.
[src:biological-process/adaptation] The peacock's ornamental train (grown anew in time for each mating season) is a famous adaptation.
[src:biological-process/adaptation] It must reduce his maneuverability and flight, and is hugely conspicuous; also, its growth costs food resources.
[src:biological-process/adaptation] The recognition of sexual selection was for a long time in abeyance, but has been rehabilitated.
[src:biological-process/adaptation] The conflict between the size of the human foetal brain at birth, (which cannot be larger than about 400 cm3, else it will not get through the mother's pelvis) and the size needed for an adult brain (about 1400 cm3), means the brain of a newborn child is quite immature.
[src:biological-process/adaptation] The most vital things in human life (locomotion, speech) just have to wait while the brain grows and matures.
[src:biological-process/adaptation] That is the result of the birth compromise.
[src:biological-process/adaptation] Much of the problem comes from our upright bipedal stance, without which our pelvis could be shaped more suitably for birth.
[src:biological-process/adaptation] As another example, the long neck of a giraffe brings benefits but at a cost.
[src:biological-process/adaptation] The neck of a giraffe can be up to 2 m (6 ft 7 in) in length.
[src:biological-process/adaptation] The benefits are that it can be used for inter-species competition or for foraging on tall trees where shorter herbivores cannot reach.
[src:biological-process/adaptation] The cost is that a long neck is heavy and adds to the animal's body mass, requiring additional energy to build the neck and to carry its weight around.
[src:biological-process/adaptation] Pre-adaptation occurs when a population has characteristics which by chance are suited for a set of conditions not previously experienced.
[src:biological-process/adaptation] For example, the polyploid cordgrass *Spartina townsendii* is better adapted than either of its parent species to their own habitat of saline marsh and mud-flats.
[src:biological-process/adaptation] Among domestic animals, the White Leghorn chicken is markedly more resistant to vitamin B1 deficiency than other breeds; on a plentiful diet this makes no difference, but on a restricted diet this preadaptation could be decisive.
[src:biological-process/adaptation] Pre-adaptation may arise because a natural population carries a huge quantity of genetic variability.
[src:biological-process/adaptation] In diploid eukaryotes, this is a consequence of the system of sexual reproduction, where mutant alleles get partially shielded, for example, by genetic dominance.
[src:biological-process/adaptation] Microorganisms, with their huge populations, also carry a great deal of genetic variability.
[src:biological-process/adaptation] The word is controversial because it is teleological and the entire concept of natural selection depends on the presence of genetic variation, regardless of the population size of a species in question.
[src:biological-process/adaptation] Features that now appear as adaptations sometimes arose by co-option of existing traits, evolved for some other purpose.
[src:biological-process/adaptation] The classic example is the ear ossicles of mammals, which we know from paleontological and embryological evidence originated in the upper and lower jaws and the hyoid bone of their synapsid ancestors, and further back still were part of the gill arches of early fish.
[src:biological-process/adaptation] The word *exaptation* was coined to cover these common evolutionary shifts in function.
[src:biological-process/adaptation] The flight feathers of birds evolved from the much earlier feathers of dinosaurs, which might have been used for insulation or for display.
[src:biological-process/adaptation] Animals including earthworms, beavers and humans use some of their adaptations to modify their surroundings, so as to maximize their chances of surviving and reproducing.
[src:biological-process/adaptation] Beavers create dams and lodges, changing the ecosystems of the valleys around them.
[src:biological-process/adaptation] Earthworms, as Darwin noted, improve the topsoil in which they live by incorporating organic matter.
[src:biological-process/adaptation] Humans have constructed extensive civilizations with cities in environments as varied as the Arctic and hot deserts.
[src:biological-process/adaptation] In all three cases, the construction and maintenance of ecological niches helps drive the continued selection of the genes of these animals, in an environment that the animals have modified.
[src:biological-process/adaptation] Some traits do not appear to be adaptive as they have a neutral or deleterious effect on fitness in the current environment.
[src:biological-process/adaptation] Another possibility is that a trait may have been adaptive at some point in an organism's evolutionary history, but a change in habitats caused what used to be an adaptation to become unnecessary or even maladapted.
[src:biological-process/adaptation] Many organisms have vestigial organs, which are the remnants of fully functional structures in their ancestors.
[src:biological-process/adaptation] As a result of changes in lifestyle the organs became redundant, and are either not functional or reduced in functionality.
[src:biological-process/adaptation] Since any structure represents some kind of cost to the general economy of the body, an advantage may accrue from their elimination once they are not functional.
[src:biological-process/adaptation] Examples: wisdom teeth in humans; the loss of pigment and functional eyes in cave fauna; the loss of structure in endoparasites.
[src:biological-process/adaptation] If a population cannot move or change sufficiently to preserve its long-term viability, then it will become extinct, at least in that locale.
[src:biological-process/adaptation] The species may or may not survive in other locales.
[src:biological-process/adaptation] Species extinction occurs when the death rate over the entire species exceeds the birth rate for a long enough period for the species to disappear.
[src:biological-process/adaptation] It was an observation of Van Valen that groups of species tend to have a characteristic and fairly regular rate of extinction.
[src:biological-process/adaptation] The first stage in the evolution of life on earth is often hypothesized to be the RNA world in which short self-replicating RNA molecules proliferated before the evolution of DNA and proteins.
[src:biological-process/adaptation] By this hypothesis, life started when RNA chains began to self-replicate, initiating the three mechanisms of Darwinian selection: heritability, variation of type, and competition for resources.
[src:biological-process/adaptation] The fitness of an RNA replicator (its per capita rate of increase) would likely have been a function of its intrinsic adaptive capacities, determined by its nucleotide sequence, and the availability of resources.
[src:biological-process/adaptation] The three primary adaptive capacities may have been: (1) replication with moderate fidelity, giving rise to heritability while allowing variation of type, (2) resistance to decay, and (3) acquisition of resources.
[src:biological-process/adaptation] These adaptive capacities would have been determined by the folded configurations of the RNA replicators resulting from their nucleotide sequences.
[src:biological-process/adaptation] In his biology, Aristotle introduced teleology to describe the adaptedness of organisms, but without accepting the supernatural intention built into Plato's thinking, which Aristotle rejected.
[src:biological-process/adaptation] Modern biologists continue to face the same difficulty.
[src:biological-process/adaptation] On the one hand, adaptation is purposeful: natural selection chooses what works and eliminates what does not.
[src:biological-process/adaptation] On the other hand, biologists by and large reject conscious purpose in evolution.
[src:biological-process/adaptation] The dilemma gave rise to a famous joke by the evolutionary biologist Haldane: "Teleology is like a mistress to a biologist: he cannot live without her but he's unwilling to be seen with her in public.'" David Hull commented that Haldane's mistress "has become a lawfully wedded wife.
[src:biological-process/adaptive-radiation] In evolutionary biology, **adaptive radiation** is a process in which organisms diversify rapidly from an ancestral species into a multitude of new forms, particularly when a change in the environment makes new resources available, alters biotic interactions or opens new environmental niches.
[src:biological-process/adaptive-radiation] Starting with a single ancestor, this process results in the speciation and phenotypic adaptation of an array of species exhibiting different morphological and physiological traits.
[src:biological-process/adaptive-radiation] The prototypical example of adaptive radiation is finch speciation on the Galapagos ("Darwin's finches"), but examples are known from around the world.
[src:biological-process/adaptive-radiation] A phenotype-environment correlation: a *significant* association between environments and the morphological and physiological traits used to exploit those environments.
[src:biological-process/adaptive-radiation] Trait utility: the performance or fitness advantages of trait values in their corresponding environments.
[src:biological-process/adaptive-radiation] Rapid speciation: presence of one or more *bursts* in the emergence of new species around the time that ecological and phenotypic divergence is underway.
[src:biological-process/adaptive-radiation] Adaptive radiations are thought to be triggered by an ecological opportunity or a new adaptive zone.
[src:biological-process/adaptive-radiation] Sources of ecological opportunity can be the loss of antagonists (competitors or predators), the evolution of a key innovation, or dispersal to a new environment.
[src:biological-process/adaptive-radiation] Any one of these ecological opportunities has the potential to result in an increase in population size and relaxed stabilizing (constraining) selection.
[src:biological-process/adaptive-radiation] As genetic diversity is positively correlated with population size the expanded population will have more genetic diversity compared to the ancestral population.
[src:biological-process/adaptive-radiation] With reduced stabilizing selection phenotypic diversity can also increase.
[src:biological-process/adaptive-radiation] In addition, intraspecific competition will increase, promoting divergent selection to use a wider range of resources.
[src:biological-process/adaptive-radiation] This ecological release provides the potential for ecological speciation and thus adaptive radiation.
[src:biological-process/adaptive-radiation] This new habitat is relatively isolated.
[src:biological-process/adaptive-radiation] When a volcano erupts on the mainland and destroys an adjacent forest, it is likely that the terrestrial plant and animal species that used to live in the destroyed region will recolonize without evolving greatly.
[src:biological-process/adaptive-radiation] However, if a newly formed habitat is isolated, the species that colonize it will likely be somewhat random and uncommon arrivals.
[src:biological-process/adaptive-radiation] The new habitat has a wide availability of niche space.
[src:biological-process/adaptive-radiation] The rare colonist can only adaptively radiate into as many forms as there are niches.
[src:biological-process/adaptive-radiation] A 2020 study found there to be no direct causal relationship between the proportionally most comparable mass radiations and extinctions in terms of "co-occurrence of species", substantially challenging the hypothesis of "creative mass extinctions".
[src:biological-process/adaptive-radiation] Darwin's finches on the Galapagos Islands are a model system for the study of adaptive radiation.
[src:biological-process/adaptive-radiation] Today represented by approximately 15 species, Darwin's finches are Galapagos endemics famously adapted for a specialized feeding behavior (although one species, the Cocos finch (*Pinaroloxias inornata*), is not found in the Galapagos but on the island of Cocos south of Costa Rica).
[src:biological-process/adaptive-radiation] Darwin's finches are not actually finches in the true sense, but are members of the tanager family Thraupidae, and are derived from a single ancestor that arrived in the Galapagos from mainland South America perhaps just 3 million years ago.
[src:biological-process/adaptive-radiation] Excluding the Cocos finch, each species of Darwin's finch is generally widely distributed in the Galapagos and fills the same niche on each island.
[src:biological-process/adaptive-radiation] For the ground finches, this niche is a diet of seeds, and they have thick bills to facilitate the consumption of these hard materials.
[src:biological-process/adaptive-radiation] There is some overlap: for example, the most robust medium ground finches could have beaks larger than those of the smallest large ground finches.
[src:biological-process/adaptive-radiation] Because of this overlap, it can be difficult to tell the species apart by eye, though their songs differ.
[src:biological-process/adaptive-radiation] These three species often occur sympatrically, and during the rainy season in the Galapagos when food is plentiful, they specialize little and eat the same, easily accessible foods.
[src:biological-process/adaptive-radiation] The other finches in the Galapagos are similarly uniquely adapted for their particular niche.
[src:biological-process/adaptive-radiation] The cactus finches (*Geospiza* sp.) have somewhat longer beaks than the ground finches that serve the dual purpose of allowing them to feed on Opuntia cactus nectar and pollen while these plants are flowering, but on seeds during the rest of the year.
[src:biological-process/adaptive-radiation] The warbler-finches (*Certhidea* sp.) have short, pointed beaks for eating insects.
[src:biological-process/adaptive-radiation] The woodpecker finch (*Camarhynchus pallidus*) has a slender beak which it uses to pick at wood in search of insects; it also uses small sticks to reach insect prey inside the wood, making it one of the few animals that use tools.
[src:biological-process/adaptive-radiation] The mechanism by which the finches initially diversified is still an area of active research.
[src:biological-process/adaptive-radiation] One proposition is that the finches were able to have a non-adaptive, allopatric speciation event on separate islands in the archipelago, such that when they reconverged on some islands, they were able to maintain reproductive isolation.
[src:biological-process/adaptive-radiation] Once they occurred in sympatry, niche specialization was favored so that the different species competed less directly for resources.
[src:biological-process/adaptive-radiation] This second, sympatric event was adaptive radiation.
[src:biological-process/adaptive-radiation] The haplochromine cichlid fishes in the Great Lakes of the East African Rift (particularly in Lake Tanganyika, Lake Malawi, and Lake Victoria) form the most speciose modern example of adaptive radiation.
[src:biological-process/adaptive-radiation] These lakes are believed to be home to about 2,000 different species of cichlid, spanning a wide range of ecological roles and morphological characteristics.
[src:biological-process/adaptive-radiation] Cichlids in these lakes fill nearly all of the roles typically filled by many fish families, including those of predators, scavengers, and herbivores, with varying dentitions and head shapes to match their dietary habits.
[src:biological-process/adaptive-radiation] In each case, the radiation events are only a few million years old, making the high level of speciation particularly remarkable.
[src:biological-process/adaptive-radiation] Several factors could be responsible for this diversity: the availability of a multitude of niches probably favored specialization, as few other fish taxa are present in the lakes (meaning that sympatric speciation was the most probable mechanism for initial specialization).
[src:biological-process/adaptive-radiation] Also, continual changes in the water level of the lakes during the Pleistocene (which often turned the largest lakes into several smaller ones) could have created the conditions for secondary allopatric speciation.
[src:biological-process/adaptive-radiation] Lake Tanganyika is the site from which nearly all the cichlid lineages of East Africa (including both riverine and lake species) originated.
[src:biological-process/adaptive-radiation] Thus, the species in the lake constitute a single adaptive radiation event but do not form a single monophyletic clade.
[src:biological-process/adaptive-radiation] Lake Tanganyika itself is believed to have formed 9–12 million years ago, putting a recent cap on the age of the lake's cichlid fauna.
[src:biological-process/adaptive-radiation] Many of Tanganyika's cichlids live very specialized lifestyles.
[src:biological-process/adaptive-radiation] The giant or emperor cichlid (*Boulengerochromis microlepis*) is a piscivore often ranked the largest of all cichlids (though it competes for this title with South America's *Cichla temensis*, the speckled peacock bass).
[src:biological-process/adaptive-radiation] It is thought that giant cichlids spawn only a single time, breeding in their third year and defending their young until they reach a large size, before dying of starvation some time thereafter.
[src:biological-process/adaptive-radiation] The three species of *Altolamprologus* are also piscivores, but with laterally compressed bodies and thick scales enabling them to chase prey into thin cracks in rocks without damaging their skin.
[src:biological-process/adaptive-radiation] *Plecodus straeleni* has evolved large, strangely curved teeth that are designed to scrape scales off of the sides of other fish, scales being its main source of food.
[src:biological-process/adaptive-radiation] *Gnathochromis permaxillaris* possesses a large mouth with a protruding upper lip, and feeds by opening this mouth downward onto the sandy lake bottom, sucking in small invertebrates.
[src:biological-process/adaptive-radiation] A number of Tanganyika's cichlids are shell-brooders, meaning that mating pairs lay and fertilize their eggs inside of empty shells on the lake bottom.
[src:biological-process/adaptive-radiation] *Lamprologus callipterus* is a unique egg-brooding species, with 15 cm-long males amassing collections of shells and guarding them in the hopes of attracting females (about 6 cm in length) to lay eggs in these shells.
[src:biological-process/adaptive-radiation] These parasitic dwarf males never grow to the size of dominant males, and the male offspring of dominant and parasitic dwarf males grow with 100% fidelity into the form of their fathers.
[src:biological-process/adaptive-radiation] A number of other highly specialized Tanganyika cichlids exist aside from these examples, including those adapted for life in open lake water up to 200m deep.
[src:biological-process/adaptive-radiation] The cichlids of Lake Malawi constitute a "species flock" of up to 1000 endemic species.
[src:biological-process/adaptive-radiation] Only seven cichlid species in Lake Malawi are not a part of the species flock: the Eastern happy (*Astatotilapia calliptera*), the sungwa (*Serranochromis robustus*), and five tilapia species (genera *Oreochromis* and *Coptodon*).
[src:biological-process/adaptive-radiation] All of the other cichlid species in the lake are descendants of a single original colonist species, which itself was descended from Tanganyikan ancestors.
[src:biological-process/adaptive-radiation] The common ancestor of Malawi's species flock is believed to have reached the lake 3.4 million years ago at the earliest, making Malawi cichlids' diversification into their present numbers particularly rapid.
[src:biological-process/adaptive-radiation] Malawi's cichlids span a similarly range of feeding behaviors to those of Tanganyika, but also show signs of a much more recent origin.
[src:biological-process/adaptive-radiation] Males of most species display predominantly blue coloration when mating.
[src:biological-process/adaptive-radiation] Lake Victoria's cichlids are also a species flock, once composed of some 500 or more species.
[src:biological-process/adaptive-radiation] The deliberate introduction of the Nile Perch (*Lates niloticus*) in the 1950s proved disastrous for Victoria cichlids, and the collective biomass of the Victoria cichlid species flock has decreased substantially and an unknown number of species have become extinct.
[src:biological-process/adaptive-radiation] However, the original range of morphological and behavioral diversity seen in the lake's cichlid fauna is still mostly present today, if endangered.
[src:biological-process/adaptive-radiation] These again include cichlids specialized for niches across the trophic spectrum, as in Tanganyika and Malawi, but again, there are standouts.
[src:biological-process/adaptive-radiation] Victoria is famously home to many piscivorous cichlid species, some of which feed by sucking the contents out of mouthbrooding females' mouths.
[src:biological-process/adaptive-radiation] Victoria's cichlids constitute a far younger radiation than even that of Lake Malawi, with estimates of the age of the flock ranging from 200,000 years to as little as 14,000.
[src:biological-process/adaptive-radiation] Hawaii has served as the site of a number of adaptive radiation events, owing to its isolation, recent origin, and large land area.
[src:biological-process/adaptive-radiation] The three most famous examples of these radiations are presented below, though insects like the Hawaiian drosophilid flies and *Hyposmocoma* moths have also undergone adaptive radiation.
[src:biological-process/adaptive-radiation] The Hawaiian honeycreepers form a large, highly morphologically diverse species group of birds that began radiating in the early days of the Hawaiian archipelago.
[src:biological-process/adaptive-radiation] While today only 17 species are known to persist in Hawaii (3 more may or may not be extinct), there were more than 50 species prior to Polynesian colonization of the archipelago (between 18 and 21 species have gone extinct since the discovery of the islands by westerners).
[src:biological-process/adaptive-radiation] Meanwhile, the ʻiʻiwi (*Drepanis coccinea*) has a very long curved beak for reaching nectar deep in *Lobelia* flowers.
[src:biological-process/adaptive-radiation] An entire clade of Hawaiian honeycreepers, the tribe Psittirostrini, is composed of thick-billed, mostly seed-eating birds, like the Laysan finch (*Telespiza cantans*).
[src:biological-process/adaptive-radiation] In at least some cases, similar morphologies and behaviors appear to have evolved convergently among the Hawaiian honeycreepers; for example, the short, pointed beaks of *Loxops* and *Oreomystis* evolved separately despite once forming the justification for lumping the two genera together.
[src:biological-process/adaptive-radiation] The Hawaiian honeycreepers are believed to have descended from a single common ancestor some 15 to 20 million years ago, though estimates range as low as 3.5 million years.
[src:biological-process/adaptive-radiation] Adaptive radiation is not a strictly vertebrate phenomenon, and examples are also known from among plants.
[src:biological-process/adaptive-radiation] The most famous example of adaptive radiation in plants is quite possibly the Hawaiian silverswords, named for alpine desert-dwelling *Argyroxiphium* species with long, silvery leaves that live for up to 20 years before growing a single flowering stalk and then dying.
[src:biological-process/adaptive-radiation] The Hawaiian silversword alliance consists of twenty-eight species of Hawaiian plants which, aside from the eponymous silverswords, includes trees, shrubs, vines, cushion plants, and more.
[src:biological-process/adaptive-radiation] The silversword alliance is believed to have originated in Hawaii no more than 6 million years ago, making this one of Hawaii's youngest adaptive radiation events.
[src:biological-process/adaptive-radiation] This means that the silverswords evolved on Hawaii's modern high islands, and descended from a single common ancestor that arrived on Kauaʻi from western North America.
[src:biological-process/adaptive-radiation] The closest modern relatives of the silverswords today are California tarweeds of the family Asteraceae.
[src:biological-process/adaptive-radiation] Hawaii is also the site of a separate major floral adaptive radiation event: the Hawaiian lobelioids.
[src:biological-process/adaptive-radiation] The Hawaiian lobelioids are significantly more speciose than the silverswords, perhaps because they have been present in Hawaii for so much longer: they descended from a single common ancestor who arrived in the archipelago up to 15 million years ago.
[src:biological-process/adaptive-radiation] Today the Hawaiian lobelioids form a clade of over 125 species, including succulents, trees, shrubs, epiphytes, etc.
[src:biological-process/adaptive-radiation] Many species have been lost to extinction and many of the surviving species endangered.
[src:biological-process/adaptive-radiation] Anole lizards are distributed broadly in the New World, from the Southeastern US to South America.
[src:biological-process/adaptive-radiation] With over 400 species currently recognized, often placed in a single genus (*Anolis*), they constitute one of the largest radiation events among all lizards.
[src:biological-process/adaptive-radiation] Anole radiation on the mainland has largely been a process of speciation, and is not adaptive to any great degree, but anoles on each of the Greater Antilles (Cuba, Hispaniola, Puerto Rico, and Jamaica) have adaptively radiated in separate, convergent ways.
[src:biological-process/adaptive-radiation] On each of these islands, anoles have evolved with such a consistent set of morphological adaptations that each species can be assigned to one of six "ecomorphs": trunk–ground, trunk–crown, grass–bush, crown–giant, twig, and trunk.
[src:biological-process/adaptive-radiation] Take for example crown–giants from each of these islands: the Cuban *Anolis luteogularis*, Hispaniola's *Anolis ricordii*, Puerto Rico's *Anolis cuvieri*, and Jamaica's *Anolis garmani* (Cuba and Hispaniola are both home to more than one species of crown–giant).
[src:biological-process/adaptive-radiation] The same can be said of the other five ecomorphs across the Caribbean's four largest islands.
[src:biological-process/adaptive-radiation] Much like in the case of the cichlids of the three largest African Great Lakes, each of these islands is home to its own convergent *Anolis* adaptive radiation event.
[src:biological-process/adaptive-radiation] Presented above are the most well-documented examples of modern adaptive radiation, but other examples are known.
[src:biological-process/adaptive-radiation] Populations of three-spined sticklebacks have repeatedly diverged and evolved into distinct ecotypes.
[src:biological-process/adaptive-radiation] On Madagascar, birds of the family Vangidae are marked by very distinct beak shapes to suit their ecological roles.
[src:biological-process/adaptive-radiation] The pseudoxyrhophiine snakes of Madagascar have evolved into fossorial, arboreal, terrestrial, and semi-aquatic forms that converge with the colubroid faunas in the rest of the world.
[src:biological-process/adaptive-radiation] These Madagascan examples are significantly older than most of the other examples presented here: Madagascar's fauna has been evolving in isolation since the island split from India some 88 million years ago, and the Mantellidae originated around 50 mya.
[src:biological-process/adaptive-radiation] Older examples are known: the K-Pg extinction event, which caused the disappearance of the dinosaurs and most other reptilian megafauna 65 million years ago, is seen as having triggered a global adaptive radiation event that created the mammal diversity that exists today.
[src:biological-process/adaptive-radiation] Also the Cambrian Explosion, where vacant niches left by the extinction of Ediacaran biota during End-Ediacaran mass extinction were filled up by the emergence of new phyla.
[src:biological-process/allopatric-speciation] Various geographic changes can arise such as the movement of continents, and the formation of mountains, islands, bodies of water, or glaciers.
[src:biological-process/allopatric-speciation] Human activity such as agriculture or developments can also change the distribution of species populations.
[src:biological-process/allopatric-speciation] These factors can substantially alter a region's geography, resulting in the separation of a species population into isolated subpopulations.
[src:biological-process/allopatric-speciation] The vicariant populations then undergo genetic changes as they become subjected to different selective pressures, experience genetic drift, and accumulate different mutations in the separated populations' gene pools.
[src:biological-process/allopatric-speciation] The barriers prevent the exchange of genetic information between the two populations leading to reproductive isolation.
[src:biological-process/allopatric-speciation] If the two populations come into contact they will be unable to reproduce—effectively speciating.
[src:biological-process/allopatric-speciation] Other isolating factors such as population dispersal leading to emigration can cause speciation (for instance, the dispersal and isolation of a species on an oceanic island) and is considered a special case of allopatric speciation called peripatric speciation.
[src:biological-process/allopatric-speciation] Allopatric speciation is typically subdivided into two major models: vicariance and peripatric.
[src:biological-process/allopatric-speciation] These models differ from one another by virtue of their population sizes and geographic isolating mechanisms.
[src:biological-process/allopatric-speciation] The terms *allopatry* and *vicariance* are often used in biogeography to describe the relationship between organisms whose ranges do not significantly overlap, but are immediately adjacent to each other; they do not occur together or only occur within a narrow zone of contact.
[src:biological-process/allopatric-speciation] Historically, the language used to refer to modes of speciation directly reflected biogeographical distributions.
[src:biological-process/allopatric-speciation] As such, allopatry is a geographical distribution opposed to sympatry (speciation within the same area).
[src:biological-process/allopatric-speciation] Furthermore, the terms allopatric, vicariant, and geographical speciation are often used interchangeably in the scientific literature.
[src:biological-process/allopatric-speciation] This article will follow a similar theme, with the exception of special cases such as peripatric, centrifugal, among others.
[src:biological-process/allopatric-speciation] Observation of nature creates difficulties in witnessing allopatric speciation from "start-to-finish" as it operates as a dynamic process.
[src:biological-process/allopatric-speciation] From this arises a host of issues in defining species, defining isolating barriers, measuring reproductive isolation, among others.
[src:biological-process/allopatric-speciation] Nevertheless, verbal and mathematical models, laboratory experiments, and empirical evidence overwhelmingly supports the occurrence of allopatric speciation in nature.
[src:biological-process/allopatric-speciation] Mathematical modeling of the genetic basis of reproductive isolation supports the plausibility of allopatric speciation; whereas laboratory experiments of *Drosophila* and other animal and plant species have confirmed that reproductive isolation evolves as a byproduct of natural selection.
[src:biological-process/allopatric-speciation] The notion of vicariant evolution was first developed by Venezuelan botanist Léon Croizat in the mid-twentieth century.
[src:biological-process/allopatric-speciation] Currently, speciation by vicariance is widely regarded as the most common form of speciation; and is the primary model of allopatric speciation.
[src:biological-process/allopatric-speciation] Vicariance is a process by which the geographical range of an individual taxon, or a whole biota, is split into discontinuous populations (disjunct distributions) by the formation of an extrinsic barrier to the exchange of genes: that is, a barrier arising externally to a species.
[src:biological-process/allopatric-speciation] Vicariant barriers can change the distribution of species populations.
[src:biological-process/allopatric-speciation] Suitable or unsuitable habitat may be come into existence, expand, contract, or disappear as a result of global climate change or even large scale human activities (for example, agricultural, civil engineering developments, and habitat fragmentation).
[src:biological-process/allopatric-speciation] Such factors can alter a region's geography in substantial ways, resulting in the separation of a species population into isolated subpopulations.
[src:biological-process/allopatric-speciation] The vicariant populations may then undergo genotypic or phenotypic divergence as: (a) different mutations arise in the gene pools of the populations, (b) they become subjected to different selective pressures, and/or (c) they independently undergo genetic drift.
[src:biological-process/allopatric-speciation] The extrinsic barriers prevent the exchange of genetic information between the two populations, potentially leading to differentiation due to the ecologically different habitats they experience; selective pressure then invariably leads to complete reproductive isolation.
[src:biological-process/allopatric-speciation] Furthermore, a species' proclivity to remain in its ecological niche (see phylogenetic niche conservatism) through changing environmental conditions may also play a role in isolating populations from one another, driving the evolution of new lineages.
[src:biological-process/allopatric-speciation] Allopatric speciation can be represented as the extreme on a gene flow continuum.
[src:biological-process/allopatric-speciation] As such, the level of gene flow between populations in allopatry would be $m=0$ , where m equals the rate of gene exchange.
[src:biological-process/allopatric-speciation] In sympatry $m=0.5$ (panmixis), while in parapatric speciation, $0<m<0.5$ represents the entire continuum, although some scientists argue that a classification scheme based solely on geographic mode does not necessarily reflect the complexity of speciation.
[src:biological-process/allopatric-speciation] Allopatry is often regarded as the default or "null" model of speciation, but this too is debated.
[src:biological-process/allopatric-speciation] Reproductive isolation acts as the primary mechanism driving genetic divergence in allopatry and can be amplified by divergent selection.
[src:biological-process/allopatric-speciation] Pre-zygotic and post-zygotic isolation are often the most cited mechanisms for allopatric speciation, and as such, it is difficult to determine which form evolved first in an allopatric speciation event.
[src:biological-process/allopatric-speciation] Pre-zygotic simply implies the presence of a barrier prior to any act of fertilization (such as an environmental barrier dividing two populations), while post-zygotic implies the prevention of successful inter-population crossing after fertilization (such as the production of an infertile hybrid).
[src:biological-process/allopatric-speciation] Since species pairs which diverged in allopatry often exhibit pre- and post-zygotic isolation mechanisms, investigation of the earliest stages in the life cycle of the species can indicate whether or not divergence occurred due to a pre-zygotic or post-zygotic factor.
[src:biological-process/allopatric-speciation] However, establishing the specific mechanism may not be accurate, as a species pair continually diverges over time.
[src:biological-process/allopatric-speciation] For example, if a plant experiences a chromosome duplication event, reproduction will occur, but sterile hybrids will result—functioning as a form of post-zygotic isolation.
[src:biological-process/allopatric-speciation] Subsequently, the newly formed species pair may experience pre-zygotic barriers to reproduction as selection, acting on each species independently, will ultimately lead to genetic changes making hybrids impossible.
[src:biological-process/allopatric-speciation] From the researcher's perspective, the current isolating mechanism may not reflect the past isolating mechanism.
[src:biological-process/allopatric-speciation] Reinforcement has been a contentious factor in speciation.
[src:biological-process/allopatric-speciation] It is more often invoked in sympatric speciation studies, as it requires gene flow between two populations.
[src:biological-process/allopatric-speciation] However, reinforcement may also play a role in allopatric speciation, whereby the reproductive barrier is removed, reuniting the two previously isolated populations.
[src:biological-process/allopatric-speciation] Upon secondary contact, individuals reproduce, creating low-fitness hybrids.
[src:biological-process/allopatric-speciation] Traits of the hybrids drive individuals to discriminate in mate choice, by which pre-zygotic isolation increases between the populations.
[src:biological-process/allopatric-speciation] Some arguments have been put forth that suggest the hybrids themselves can possibly become their own species: known as hybrid speciation.
[src:biological-process/allopatric-speciation] Reinforcement can play a role in all geographic modes (and other non-geographic modes) of speciation as long as gene flow is present and viable hybrids can be formed.
[src:biological-process/allopatric-speciation] The production of inviable hybrids is a form of reproductive character displacement, under which most definitions is the completion of a speciation event.
[src:biological-process/allopatric-speciation] Research has well established the fact that interspecific mate discrimination occurs to a greater extent between sympatric populations than it does in purely allopatric populations; however, other factors have been proposed to account for the observed patterns.
[src:biological-process/allopatric-speciation] Reinforcement in allopatry has been shown to occur in nature (evidence for speciation by reinforcement), albeit with less frequency than a classic allopatric speciation event.
[src:biological-process/allopatric-speciation] A major difficulty arises when interpreting reinforcement's role in allopatric speciation, as current phylogenetic patterns may suggest past gene flow.
[src:biological-process/allopatric-speciation] This masks possible initial divergence in allopatry and can indicate a "mixed-mode" speciation event—exhibiting both allopatric and sympatric speciation processes.
[src:biological-process/allopatric-speciation] Developed in the context of the genetic basis of reproductive isolation, mathematical scenarios model both prezygotic and postzygotic isolation with respect to the effects of genetic drift, selection, sexual selection, or various combinations of the three.
[src:biological-process/allopatric-speciation] Masatoshi Nei and colleagues were the first to develop a neutral, stochastic model of speciation by genetic drift alone.
[src:biological-process/allopatric-speciation] Both selection and drift can lead to postzygotic isolation, supporting the fact that two geographically separated populations can evolve reproductive isolation—sometimes occurring rapidly.
[src:biological-process/allopatric-speciation] Fisherian sexual selection can also lead to reproductive isolation if there are minor variations in selective pressures (such as predation risks or habitat differences) among each population.
[src:biological-process/allopatric-speciation] (See the Further reading section below).
[src:biological-process/allopatric-speciation] Mathematical models concerning reproductive isolation-by distance have shown that populations can experience increasing reproductive isolation that correlates directly with physical, geographical distance.
[src:biological-process/allopatric-speciation] This has been exemplified in models of ring species; however, it has been argued that ring species are a special case, representing reproductive isolation-by distance, and demonstrate parapatric speciation instead—as parapatric speciation represents speciation occurring along a cline.
[src:biological-process/allopatric-speciation] Various alternative models have been developed concerning allopatric speciation.
[src:biological-process/allopatric-speciation] Other minor allopatric models have also been developed are discussed below.
[src:biological-process/allopatric-speciation] Peripatric speciation is a mode of speciation in which a new species is formed from an isolated peripheral population.
[src:biological-process/allopatric-speciation] If a small population of a species becomes isolated (*e.g.* a population of birds on an oceanic island), selection can act on the population independent of the parent population.
[src:biological-process/allopatric-speciation] Given both geographic separation and enough time, speciation can result as a byproduct.
[src:biological-process/allopatric-speciation] It can be distinguished from allopatric speciation by three important features: 1) the size of the isolated population, 2) the strong selection imposed by the dispersal and colonization into novel environments, and 3) the potential effects of genetic drift on small populations.
[src:biological-process/allopatric-speciation] However, it can often be difficult for researchers to determine if peripatric speciation occurred as vicariant explanations can be invoked due to the fact that both models posit the absence of gene flow between the populations.
[src:biological-process/allopatric-speciation] The size of the isolated population is important because individuals colonizing a new habitat likely contain only a small sample of the genetic variation of the original population.
[src:biological-process/allopatric-speciation] This promotes divergence due to strong selective pressures, leading to the rapid fixation of an allele within the descendant population.
[src:biological-process/allopatric-speciation] This gives rise to the potential for genetic incompatibilities to evolve.
[src:biological-process/allopatric-speciation] These incompatibilities cause reproductive isolation, giving rise to rapid speciation events.
[src:biological-process/allopatric-speciation] Models of peripatry are supported mostly by species distribution patterns in nature.
[src:biological-process/allopatric-speciation] Oceanic islands and archipelagos provide the strongest empirical evidence that peripatric speciation occurs.
[src:biological-process/allopatric-speciation] Centrifugal speciation is a variant, alternative model of peripatric speciation.
[src:biological-process/allopatric-speciation] This model contrasts with peripatric speciation by virtue of the origin of the genetic novelty that leads to reproductive isolation.
[src:biological-process/allopatric-speciation] When a population of a species experiences a period of geographic range expansion and contraction, it may leave small, fragmented, peripherally isolated populations behind.
[src:biological-process/allopatric-speciation] These isolated populations will contain samples of the genetic variation from the larger parent population.
[src:biological-process/allopatric-speciation] This variation leads to a higher likelihood of ecological niche specialization and the evolution of reproductive isolation.
[src:biological-process/allopatric-speciation] Centrifugal speciation has been largely ignored in the scientific literature.
[src:biological-process/allopatric-speciation] Nevertheless, a wealth of evidence has been put forth by researchers in support of the model, much of which has not yet been refuted.
[src:biological-process/allopatric-speciation] One example is the possible center of origin in the Indo-West Pacific.
[src:biological-process/allopatric-speciation] Microallopatry refers to allopatric speciation occurring on a small geographic scale.
[src:biological-process/allopatric-speciation] Examples of microallopatric speciation in nature have been described.
[src:biological-process/allopatric-speciation] Rico and Turner found intralacustrine allopatric divergence of *Pseudotropheus callainos* (*Maylandia callainos*) within Lake Malawi separated only by 35 meters.
[src:biological-process/allopatric-speciation] Gustave Paulay found evidence that species in the subfamily Cryptorhynchinae have microallopatrically speciated on Rapa and its surrounding islets.
[src:biological-process/allopatric-speciation] A sympatrically distributed triplet of diving beetle (*Paroster*) species living in aquifers of Australia's Yilgarn region have likely speciated microallopatrically within a 3.5 km2 area.
[src:biological-process/allopatric-speciation] The term was originally proposed by Hobart M.
[src:biological-process/allopatric-speciation] Smith to describe a level of geographic resolution.
[src:biological-process/allopatric-speciation] A sympatric population may exist in low resolution, whereas viewed with a higher resolution (*i.e.* on a small, localized scale within the population) it is "microallopatric".
[src:biological-process/allopatric-speciation] Ben Fitzpatrick and colleagues contend that this original definition, "is misleading because it confuses geographical and ecological concepts".
[src:biological-process/allopatric-speciation] Ecological speciation can occur allopatrically, sympatrically, or parapatrically; the only requirement being that it occurs as a result of adaptation to different ecological or micro-ecological conditions.
[src:biological-process/allopatric-speciation] Ecological allopatry is a reverse-ordered form of allopatric speciation in conjunction with reinforcement.
[src:biological-process/allopatric-speciation] First, divergent selection separates a non-allopatric population emerging from pre-zygotic barriers, from which genetic differences evolve due to the obstruction of complete gene flow.
[src:biological-process/allopatric-speciation] The terms allo-parapatric and allo-sympatric have been used to describe speciation scenarios where divergence occurs in allopatry but speciation occurs only upon secondary contact.
[src:biological-process/allopatric-speciation] These are effectively models of reinforcement or "mixed-mode" speciation events.
[src:biological-process/allopatric-speciation] As allopatric speciation is widely accepted as a common mode of speciation, the scientific literature is abundant with studies documenting its existence.
[src:biological-process/allopatric-speciation] The biologist Ernst Mayr was the first to summarize the contemporary literature of the time in 1942 and 1963.
[src:biological-process/allopatric-speciation] Many of the examples he set forth remain conclusive; however, modern research supports geographic speciation with molecular phylogenetics—adding a level of robustness unavailable to early researchers.
[src:biological-process/allopatric-speciation] The most recent thorough treatment of allopatric speciation (and speciation research in general) is Jerry Coyne and H.
[src:biological-process/allopatric-speciation] Allen Orr's 2004 publication *Speciation*.
[src:biological-process/allopatric-speciation] Allopatric speciation has resulted in many of the biogeographic and biodiversity patterns found on Earth: on islands, continents, and even among mountains.
[src:biological-process/allopatric-speciation] Islands are often home to species endemics—existing only on an island and nowhere else in the world—with nearly all taxa residing on isolated islands sharing common ancestry with a species on the nearest continent.
[src:biological-process/allopatric-speciation] Not without challenge, there is typically a correlation between island endemics and diversity; that is, that the greater the diversity (species richness) of an island, the greater the increase in endemism.
[src:biological-process/allopatric-speciation] Increased diversity effectively drives speciation.
[src:biological-process/allopatric-speciation] Furthermore, the number of endemics on an island is directly correlated with the relative isolation of the island and its area.
[src:biological-process/allopatric-speciation] In some cases, speciation on islands has occurred rapidly.
[src:biological-process/allopatric-speciation] Dispersal and *in situ* speciation are the agents that explain the origins of the organisms in Hawaii.
[src:biological-process/allopatric-speciation] Various geographic modes of speciation have been studied extensively in Hawaiian biota, and in particular, angiosperms appear to have speciated predominately in allopatric and parapatric modes.
[src:biological-process/allopatric-speciation] Islands are not the only geographic locations that have endemic species.
[src:biological-process/allopatric-speciation] South America has been studied extensively with its areas of endemism representing assemblages of allopatrically distributed species groups.
[src:biological-process/allopatric-speciation] *Charis* butterflies are a primary example, confined to specific regions corresponding to phylogenies of other species of butterflies, amphibians, birds, marsupials, primates, reptiles, and rodents.
[src:biological-process/allopatric-speciation] The pattern indicates repeated vicariant speciation events among these groups.
[src:biological-process/allopatric-speciation] It is thought that rivers may play a role as the geographic barriers to *Charis*, not unlike the river barrier hypothesis used to explain the high rates of diversity in the Amazon basin—though this hypothesis has been disputed.
[src:biological-process/allopatric-speciation] Dispersal-mediated allopatric speciation is also thought to be a significant driver of diversification throughout the Neotropics.
[src:biological-process/allopatric-speciation] Patterns of increased endemism at higher elevations on both islands and continents have been documented on a global level.
[src:biological-process/allopatric-speciation] As topographical elevation increases, species become isolated from one another; often constricted to graded zones.
[src:biological-process/allopatric-speciation] This isolation on "mountain top islands" creates barriers to gene flow, encouraging allopatric speciation, and generating the formation of endemic species.
[src:biological-process/allopatric-speciation] Mountain building (orogeny) is directly correlated with—and directly affects biodiversity.
[src:biological-process/allopatric-speciation] The formation of the Himalayan mountains and the Qinghai–Tibetan Plateau for example have driven the speciation and diversification of numerous plants and animals such as *Lepisorus* ferns; glyptosternoid fishes (Sisoridae); and the *Rana chensinensis* species complex.
[src:biological-process/allopatric-speciation] Uplift has also driven vicariant speciation in *Macowania* daisies in South Africa's Drakensberg mountains, along with *Dendrocincla* woodcreepers in the South American Andes.
[src:biological-process/allopatric-speciation] The Laramide orogeny during the Late Cretaceous even caused vicariant speciation and radiations of dinosaurs in North America.
[src:biological-process/allopatric-speciation] Adaptive radiation, like the Galapagos finches observed by Charles Darwin, is often a consequence of rapid allopatric speciation among populations.
[src:biological-process/allopatric-speciation] However, in the case of the finches of the Galapagos, among other island radiations such as the honeycreepers of Hawaii represent cases of limited geographic separation and were likely driven by ecological speciation.
[src:biological-process/allopatric-speciation] Geological evidence supports the final closure of the isthmus of Panama approximately 2.7 to 3.5 mya, with some evidence suggesting an earlier transient bridge existing between 13 and 15 mya.
[src:biological-process/allopatric-speciation] Recent evidence increasingly points towards an older and more complex emergence of the Isthmus, with fossil and extant species dispersal (part of the American biotic interchange) occurring in three major pulses, to and from North and South America.
[src:biological-process/allopatric-speciation] Further, the changes in terrestrial biotic distributions of both continents such as with *Eciton* army ants supports an earlier bridge or a series of bridges.
[src:biological-process/allopatric-speciation] Regardless of the exact timing of the isthmus closer, biologists can study the species on the Pacific and Caribbean sides in what has been called, "one of the greatest natural experiments in evolution".
[src:biological-process/allopatric-speciation] Additionally, as with most geologic events, the closure was unlikely to have occurred rapidly, but instead dynamically—a gradual shallowing of sea water over millions of years.
[src:biological-process/allopatric-speciation] Recently diverged species live in shallow mangrove waters while older diverged species live in deeper water, correlating with a gradual closure of the isthmus.
[src:biological-process/allopatric-speciation] Support for an allopatric divergence also comes from laboratory experiments on the species pairs showing nearly complete reproductive isolation.
[src:biological-process/allopatric-speciation] Ice ages have played important roles in facilitating speciation among vertebrate species.
[src:biological-process/allopatric-speciation] This concept of refugia has been applied to numerous groups of species and their biogeographic distributions.
[src:biological-process/allopatric-speciation] (i.) schistacea*); *Vireo* (*V. plumbeus*, *V. cassinii*, and *V. solitarius*); *tyrant flycatchers* (*E. occidentalis* and *E. difficilis*); *chickadees* (*P. rufescens* and *P. hudsonicus*); and *thrushes* (*C. bicknelli* and *C. minimus*).
[src:biological-process/allopatric-speciation] Numerous species pairs or species groups show abutting distribution patterns, that is, reside in geographically distinct regions next to each other.
[src:biological-process/allopatric-speciation] They often share borders, many of which contain hybrid zones.
[src:biological-process/allopatric-speciation] In birds, some areas are prone to high rates of superspecies formation such as the 105 superspecies in Melanesia, comprising 66 percent of all bird species in the region.
[src:biological-process/allopatric-speciation] Patagonia is home to 17 superspecies of forest birds, while North America has 127 superspecies of both land and freshwater birds.
[src:biological-process/allopatric-speciation] Sub-Saharan Africa has 486 passerine birds grouped into 169 superspecies.
[src:biological-process/allopatric-speciation] Australia has numerous bird superspecies as well, with 34 percent of all bird species grouped into superspecies.
[src:biological-process/allopatric-speciation] Experiments on allopatric speciation are often complex and do not simply divide a species population into two.
[src:biological-process/allopatric-speciation] This is due to a host of defining parameters: measuring reproductive isolation, sample sizes (the number of matings conducted in reproductive isolation tests), bottlenecks, length of experiments, number of generations allowed, or insufficient genetic diversity.
[src:biological-process/allopatric-speciation] Here, A and D represent the number of matings in heterogameticity where B and C represent homogametic matings.
[src:biological-process/allopatric-speciation] A and B is one population and D and C is the second population.
[src:biological-process/allopatric-speciation] A negative value of Y denotes negative assortive mating, a positive value denotes positive assortive mating (i. e. expressing reproductive isolation), and a null value (of zero) means the populations are experiencing random mating.
[src:biological-process/allopatric-speciation] The experimental evidence has solidly established the fact that reproductive isolation evolves as a by-product of selection.
[src:biological-process/allopatric-speciation] Reproductive isolation has been shown to arise from pleiotropy (*i.e.* indirect selection acting on genes that code for more than one trait)—what has been referred to as genetic hitchhiking.
[src:biological-process/allopatric-speciation] Limitations and controversies exist relating to whether laboratory experiments can accurately reflect the long-scale process of allopatric speciation that occurs in nature.
[src:biological-process/allopatric-speciation] Experiments often fall beneath 100 generations, far less than expected, as rates of speciation in nature are thought to be much larger.
[src:biological-process/allopatric-speciation] Furthermore, rates specifically concerning the evolution of reproductive isolation in *Drosophila* are significantly higher than what is practiced in laboratory settings.
[src:biological-process/allopatric-speciation] Using index *Y* presented previously, a survey of 25 allopatric speciation experiments (included in the table below) found that reproductive isolation was not as strong as typically maintained and that laboratory environments have not been well-suited for modeling allopatric speciation.
[src:biological-process/allopatric-speciation] Nevertheless, numerous experiments have shown pre-zygotic and post-zygotic isolation in vicariance, some in less than 100 generations.
[src:biological-process/allopatric-speciation] Below is a non-exhaustive table of the laboratory experiments conducted on allopatric speciation.
[src:biological-process/allopatric-speciation] The first column indicates the species used in the referenced study, where the "Trait" column refers to the specific characteristic selected for or against in that species.
[src:biological-process/allopatric-speciation] The "Generations" column refers to the number of generations in each experiment performed.
[src:biological-process/allopatric-speciation] If more than one experiment was formed generations are separated by semicolons or dashes (given as a range).
[src:biological-process/allopatric-speciation] Some studies provide a duration in which the experiment was conducted.
[src:biological-process/allopatric-speciation] The "Selection type" column indicates if the study modeled vicariant or peripatric speciation (this may not be explicitly).
[src:biological-process/allopatric-speciation] Some studies performed experiments modeling or controlling for genetic drift.
[src:biological-process/allopatric-speciation] Reproductive isolation occurred pre-zygotically, post-zygotically, both, or not at all.
[src:biological-process/allopatric-speciation] Many of the studies conducted contain multiple experiments within—a resolution of which this table does not reflect.
[src:biological-process/allopatric-speciation] Early speciation research typically reflected geographic distributions and were thus termed geographic, semi-geographic, and non-geographic.
[src:biological-process/allopatric-speciation] Geographic speciation corresponds to today's usage of the term allopatric speciation, and in 1868, Moritz Wagner was the first to propose the concept of which he used the term *Separationstheorie*.
[src:biological-process/allopatric-speciation] His idea was later interpreted by Ernst Mayr as a form of founder effect speciation as it focused primarily on small geographically isolated populations.
[src:biological-process/allopatric-speciation] Edward Bagnall Poulton, an evolutionary biologist and a strong proponent of the importance of natural selection, highlighted the role of geographic isolation in promoting speciation, in the process coining the term "sympatric speciation" in 1903.
[src:biological-process/allopatric-speciation] Controversy exists as to whether Charles Darwin recognized a true geographical-based model of speciation in his publication of the *Origin of Species*.
[src:biological-process/allopatric-speciation] In chapter 11, "Geographical Distribution", Darwin discusses geographic barriers to migration, stating for example that "barriers of any kind, or obstacles to free migration, are related in a close and important manner to the differences between the productions of various regions [of the world]".
[src:biological-process/allopatric-speciation] Sulloway contends that Darwin's position on speciation was "misleading" at the least and may have later misinformed Wagner and David Starr Jordan into believing that Darwin viewed sympatric speciation as the most important mode of speciation.
[src:biological-process/allopatric-speciation] Nevertheless, Darwin never fully accepted Wagner's concept of geographical speciation.
[src:biological-process/allopatric-speciation] David Starr Jordan played a significant role in promoting allopatric speciation in the early 20th century, providing a wealth of evidence from nature to support the theory.
[src:biological-process/allopatric-speciation] Much later, the biologist Ernst Mayr was the first to encapsulate the then contemporary literature in his 1942 publication *Systematics and the Origin of Species, from the Viewpoint of a Zoologist* and in his subsequent 1963 publication *Animal Species and Evolution*.
[src:biological-process/allopatric-speciation] Like Jordan's works, they relied on direct observations of nature, documenting the occurrence of allopatric speciation, of which is widely accepted today.
[src:biological-process/allopatric-speciation] Prior to this research, Theodosius Dobzhansky published *Genetics and the Origin of Species* in 1937 where he formulated the genetic framework for how speciation could occur.
[src:biological-process/allopatric-speciation] The late 20th century saw the development of mathematical models of allopatric speciation, leading to the clear theoretical plausibility that geographic isolation can result in the reproductive isolation of two populations.
[src:biological-process/allopatric-speciation] Since the 1940s, allopatric speciation has been accepted.
[src:biological-process/allopatric-speciation] Today, it is widely regarded as the most common form of speciation taking place in nature.
[src:biological-process/allopatric-speciation] However, this is not without controversy, as both parapatric and sympatric speciation are both considered tenable modes of speciation that occur in nature.
[src:biological-process/allopatric-speciation] Contemporary research relies largely on multiple lines of evidence to determine the mode of a speciation event; that is, determining patterns of geographic distribution in conjunction with phylogenetic relatedness based on molecular techniques.
[src:biological-process/allopatric-speciation] This method was effectively introduced by John D.
[src:biological-process/allopatric-speciation] Lynch in 1986 and numerous researchers have employed it and similar methods, yielding enlightening results.
[src:biological-process/allopatric-speciation] Correlation of geographic distribution with phylogenetic data also spawned a sub-field of biogeography called vicariance biogeography developed by Joel Cracraft, James Brown, Mark V.
[src:biological-process/allopatric-speciation] Lomolino, among other biologists specializing in ecology and biogeography.
[src:biological-process/allopatric-speciation] Molecular clock dating methods are also often employed to accurately gauge divergence times that reflect the fossil or geological record (such as with the snapping shrimp separated by the closure of the Isthmus of Panama or speciation events within the genus *Cyclamen*).
[src:biological-process/allopatric-speciation] Biotechnological advances have allowed for large scale, multi-locus genome comparisons (such as with the possible allopatric speciation event that occurred between ancestral humans and chimpanzees), linking species' evolutionary history with ecology and clarifying phylogenetic patterns.
[src:biological-process/alternatives-to-darwinian-evolution] This distinguishes them from certain other kinds of arguments that deny that large-scale evolution of any sort has taken place, as in some forms of creationism, which do not propose alternative mechanisms of evolutionary change but instead deny that evolutionary change has taken place at all.
[src:biological-process/alternatives-to-darwinian-evolution] Where the fact of evolutionary change was accepted but the mechanism proposed by Charles Darwin, natural selection, was denied, explanations of evolution such as Lamarckism, catastrophism, orthogenesis, vitalism, structuralism and mutationism (called saltationism before 1900) were entertained.
[src:biological-process/alternatives-to-darwinian-evolution] Different factors motivated people to propose non-Darwinian mechanisms of evolution.
[src:biological-process/alternatives-to-darwinian-evolution] Natural selection, with its emphasis on death and competition, did not appeal to some naturalists because they felt it immoral, leaving little room for teleology or the concept of progress (orthogenesis) in the development of life.
[src:biological-process/alternatives-to-darwinian-evolution] Some who came to accept evolution, but disliked natural selection, raised religious objections.
[src:biological-process/alternatives-to-darwinian-evolution] Others felt that evolution was an inherently progressive process that natural selection alone was insufficient to explain.
[src:biological-process/alternatives-to-darwinian-evolution] Still others felt that nature, including the development of life, followed orderly patterns that natural selection could not explain.
[src:biological-process/alternatives-to-darwinian-evolution] By the start of the 20th century, evolution was generally accepted by biologists but natural selection was in eclipse.
[src:biological-process/alternatives-to-darwinian-evolution] Many alternative theories were proposed, but biologists were quick to discount theories such as orthogenesis, vitalism and Lamarckism which offered no mechanism for evolution.
[src:biological-process/alternatives-to-darwinian-evolution] Mutationism did propose a mechanism, but it was not generally accepted.
[src:biological-process/alternatives-to-darwinian-evolution] The modern synthesis a generation later claimed to sweep away all the alternatives to Darwinian evolution, though some have been revived as molecular mechanisms for them have been discovered.
[src:biological-process/alternatives-to-darwinian-evolution] Aristotle did not embrace either divine creation or evolution, instead arguing in his biology that each species (*eidos*) was immutable, breeding true to its ideal eternal form (not the same as Plato's theory of forms).
[src:biological-process/alternatives-to-darwinian-evolution] Aristotle's suggestion in *De Generatione Animalium* of a fixed hierarchy in nature - a *scala naturae* ("ladder of nature") provided an early explanation of the continuity of living things.
[src:biological-process/alternatives-to-darwinian-evolution] Aristotle saw that animals were teleological (functionally end-directed), and had parts that were homologous with those of other animals, but he did not connect these ideas into a concept of evolutionary progress.
[src:biological-process/alternatives-to-darwinian-evolution] In the Middle Ages, Scholasticism developed Aristotle's view into the idea of a great chain of being.
[src:biological-process/alternatives-to-darwinian-evolution] The image of a ladder inherently suggests the possibility of climbing, but both the ancient Greeks and mediaeval scholastics such as Ramon Llull maintained that each species remained fixed from the moment of its creation.
[src:biological-process/alternatives-to-darwinian-evolution] Accordingly, Geoffroy and later biologists looked for explanations of such evolutionary change.
[src:biological-process/alternatives-to-darwinian-evolution] Georges Cuvier's 1812 *Recherches sur les Ossements Fossiles* set out his doctrine of the correlation of parts, namely that since an organism was a whole system, all its parts mutually corresponded, contributing to the function of the whole.
[src:biological-process/alternatives-to-darwinian-evolution] So, from a single bone the zoologist could often tell what class or even genus the animal belonged to.
[src:biological-process/alternatives-to-darwinian-evolution] And if an animal had teeth adapted for cutting meat, the zoologist could be sure without even looking that its sense organs would be those of a predator and its intestines those of a carnivore.
[src:biological-process/alternatives-to-darwinian-evolution] A species had an irreducible functional complexity, and "none of its parts can change without the others changing too".
[src:biological-process/alternatives-to-darwinian-evolution] Evolutionists expected one part to change at a time, one change to follow another.
[src:biological-process/alternatives-to-darwinian-evolution] In Cuvier's view, evolution was impossible, as any one change would unbalance the whole delicate system.
[src:biological-process/alternatives-to-darwinian-evolution] Louis Agassiz's 1856 "Essay on Classification" exemplified German philosophical idealism.
[src:biological-process/alternatives-to-darwinian-evolution] This held that each species was complex within itself, had complex relationships to other organisms, and fitted precisely into its environment, as a pine tree in a forest, and could not survive outside those circles.
[src:biological-process/alternatives-to-darwinian-evolution] The argument from such ideal forms opposed evolution without offering an actual alternative mechanism.
[src:biological-process/alternatives-to-darwinian-evolution] Richard Owen held a similar view in Britain.
[src:biological-process/alternatives-to-darwinian-evolution] The Lamarckian social philosopher and evolutionist Herbert Spencer, ironically the author of the phrase "survival of the fittest" adopted by Darwin, used an argument like Cuvier's to oppose natural selection.
[src:biological-process/alternatives-to-darwinian-evolution] In 1893, he stated that a change in any one structure of the body would require all the other parts to adapt to fit in with the new arrangement.
[src:biological-process/alternatives-to-darwinian-evolution] From this, he argued that it was unlikely that all the changes could appear at the right moment if each one depended on random variation; whereas in a Lamarckian world, all the parts would naturally adapt at once, through a changed pattern of use and disuse.
[src:biological-process/alternatives-to-darwinian-evolution] (Purely religious points of view such as young or old earth creationism or intelligent design are not considered here.) Different factors motivated people to propose non-Darwinian evolutionary mechanisms.
[src:biological-process/alternatives-to-darwinian-evolution] Natural selection, with its emphasis on death and competition, did not appeal to some naturalists because they felt it immoral, leaving little room for teleology or the concept of progress in the development of life.
[src:biological-process/alternatives-to-darwinian-evolution] Some of these scientists and philosophers, like St.
[src:biological-process/alternatives-to-darwinian-evolution] George Jackson Mivart and Charles Lyell, who came to accept evolution but disliked natural selection, raised religious objections.
[src:biological-process/alternatives-to-darwinian-evolution] Others, such as the biologist and philosopher Herbert Spencer, the botanist George Henslow (son of Darwin's mentor John Stevens Henslow, also a botanist), and the author Samuel Butler, felt that evolution was an inherently progressive process that natural selection alone was insufficient to explain.
[src:biological-process/alternatives-to-darwinian-evolution] Still others, including the American paleontologists Edward Drinker Cope and Alpheus Hyatt, had an idealist perspective and felt that nature, including the development of life, followed orderly patterns that natural selection could not explain.
[src:biological-process/alternatives-to-darwinian-evolution] Another factor at the end of the 19th century was the rise of a new faction of biologists, typified by geneticists like Hugo de Vries and Thomas Hunt Morgan, who wanted to recast biology as an experimental laboratory science.
[src:biological-process/alternatives-to-darwinian-evolution] They distrusted the work of naturalists like Darwin and Alfred Russel Wallace, dependent on field observations of variation, adaptation, and biogeography, as being overly anecdotal.
[src:biological-process/alternatives-to-darwinian-evolution] Instead they focused on topics like physiology and genetics that could be investigated with controlled experiments in the laboratory, and discounted less accessible phenomena like natural selection and adaptation to the environment.
[src:biological-process/alternatives-to-darwinian-evolution] Vitalism holds that living organisms differ from other things in containing something non-physical, such as a fluid or vital spirit, that makes them live.
[src:biological-process/alternatives-to-darwinian-evolution] Since Early Modern times, vitalism stood in contrast to the mechanistic explanation of biological systems started by Descartes.
[src:biological-process/alternatives-to-darwinian-evolution] Nineteenth century chemists set out to disprove the claim that forming organic compounds required vitalist influence.
[src:biological-process/alternatives-to-darwinian-evolution] In 1828, Friedrich Wöhler showed that urea could be made entirely from inorganic chemicals.
[src:biological-process/alternatives-to-darwinian-evolution] Louis Pasteur believed that fermentation required whole organisms, which he supposed carried out chemical reactions found only in living things.
[src:biological-process/alternatives-to-darwinian-evolution] Vitalism faded out with the demonstration of more satisfactory mechanistic explanations of each of the functions of a living cell or organism.
[src:biological-process/alternatives-to-darwinian-evolution] The American botanist Asa Gray used the name "theistic evolution" for his point of view, presented in his 1876 book *Essays and Reviews Pertaining to Darwinism*.
[src:biological-process/alternatives-to-darwinian-evolution] He argued that the deity supplies beneficial mutations to guide evolution.
[src:biological-process/alternatives-to-darwinian-evolution] St George Jackson Mivart argued instead in his 1871 *On the Genesis of Species* that the deity, equipped with foreknowledge, sets the direction of evolution by specifying the (orthogenetic) laws that govern it, and leaves species to evolve according to the conditions they experience as time goes by.
[src:biological-process/alternatives-to-darwinian-evolution] The Duke of Argyll set out similar views in his 1867 book *The Reign of Law*.
[src:biological-process/alternatives-to-darwinian-evolution] According to the historian Edward Larson, the theory failed as an explanation in the minds of late 19th century biologists as it broke the rules of methodological naturalism which they had grown to expect.
[src:biological-process/alternatives-to-darwinian-evolution] Accordingly, by around 1900, biologists no longer saw theistic evolution as a valid theory.
[src:biological-process/alternatives-to-darwinian-evolution] In Larson's view, by then it "did not even merit a nod among scientists." In the 20th century, theistic evolution could take other forms, such as the orthogenesis of Teilhard de Chardin.
[src:biological-process/alternatives-to-darwinian-evolution] Orthogenesis or Progressionism is the hypothesis that life has an innate tendency to change, developing in a unilinear fashion in a particular direction, or simply making some kind of definite progress.
[src:biological-process/alternatives-to-darwinian-evolution] Many different versions have been proposed, some such as that of Teilhard de Chardin openly spiritual, others such as Theodor Eimer's apparently simply biological.
[src:biological-process/alternatives-to-darwinian-evolution] These theories often combined orthogenesis with other supposed mechanisms.
[src:biological-process/alternatives-to-darwinian-evolution] For example, Eimer believed in Lamarckian evolution, but felt that internal laws of growth determined which characteristics would be acquired and would guide the long-term direction of evolution.
[src:biological-process/alternatives-to-darwinian-evolution] Orthogenesis was popular among paleontologists such as Henry Fairfield Osborn.
[src:biological-process/alternatives-to-darwinian-evolution] They believed that the fossil record showed unidirectional change, but did not necessarily accept that the mechanism driving orthogenesis was teleological (goal-directed).
[src:biological-process/alternatives-to-darwinian-evolution] Osborn argued in his 1918 book *Origin and Evolution of Life* that trends in Titanothere horns were both orthogenetic and non-adaptive, and could be detrimental to the organism.
[src:biological-process/alternatives-to-darwinian-evolution] For instance, they supposed that the large antlers of the Irish elk had caused its extinction.
[src:biological-process/alternatives-to-darwinian-evolution] Support for orthogenesis fell during the modern synthesis in the 1940s when it became apparent that it could not explain the complex branching patterns of evolution revealed by statistical analysis of the fossil record.
[src:biological-process/alternatives-to-darwinian-evolution] Work in the 21st century has supported the mechanism and existence of mutation-biased adaptation (a form of mutationism), meaning that constrained orthogenesis is now seen as possible.
[src:biological-process/alternatives-to-darwinian-evolution] Moreover, the self-organizing processes involved in certain aspects of embryonic development often exhibit stereotypical morphological outcomes, suggesting that evolution will proceed in preferred directions once key molecular components are in place.
[src:biological-process/alternatives-to-darwinian-evolution] Jean-Baptiste Lamarck's 1809 evolutionary theory, transmutation of species, was based on a progressive (orthogenetic) drive toward greater complexity.
[src:biological-process/alternatives-to-darwinian-evolution] Lamarck also shared the belief, common at the time, that characteristics acquired during an organism's life could be inherited by the next generation, producing adaptation to the environment.
[src:biological-process/alternatives-to-darwinian-evolution] Such characteristics were caused by the use or disuse of the affected part of the body.
[src:biological-process/alternatives-to-darwinian-evolution] This minor component of Lamarck's theory became known, much later, as Lamarckism.
[src:biological-process/alternatives-to-darwinian-evolution] In the late 19th century, neo-Lamarckism was supported by the German biologist Ernst Haeckel, the American paleontologists Edward Drinker Cope and Alpheus Hyatt, and the American entomologist Alpheus Packard.
[src:biological-process/alternatives-to-darwinian-evolution] Butler and Cope believed that this allowed organisms to effectively drive their own evolution.
[src:biological-process/alternatives-to-darwinian-evolution] Packard argued that the loss of vision in the blind cave insects he studied was best explained through a Lamarckian process of atrophy through disuse combined with inheritance of acquired characteristics.
[src:biological-process/alternatives-to-darwinian-evolution] Critics pointed out that there was no solid evidence for the inheritance of acquired characteristics.
[src:biological-process/alternatives-to-darwinian-evolution] In modern epigenetics, biologists observe that phenotypes depend on heritable changes to gene expression that do not involve changes to the DNA sequence.
[src:biological-process/alternatives-to-darwinian-evolution] These changes can cross generations in plants, animals, and prokaryotes.
[src:biological-process/alternatives-to-darwinian-evolution] This is not identical to traditional Lamarckism, as the changes do not last indefinitely and do not affect the germ line and hence the evolution of genes.
[src:biological-process/alternatives-to-darwinian-evolution] Cuvier believed that the stratigraphic record indicated that there had been several such catastrophes, recurring natural events, separated by long periods of stability during the history of life on earth.
[src:biological-process/alternatives-to-darwinian-evolution] This led him to believe the Earth was several million years old.
[src:biological-process/alternatives-to-darwinian-evolution] Catastrophism has found a place in modern biology with the Cretaceous–Paleogene extinction event at the end of the Cretaceous period, as proposed in a paper by Walter and Luis Alvarez in 1980.
[src:biological-process/alternatives-to-darwinian-evolution] It argued that a 10 kilometres (6.2 mi) asteroid struck Earth 66 million years ago at the end of the Cretaceous period.
[src:biological-process/alternatives-to-darwinian-evolution] The event, whatever it was, made about 70% of all species extinct, including the dinosaurs, leaving behind the Cretaceous–Paleogene boundary.
[src:biological-process/alternatives-to-darwinian-evolution] In 1990, a 180 kilometres (110 mi) candidate crater marking the impact was identified at Chicxulub in the Yucatán Peninsula of Mexico.
[src:biological-process/alternatives-to-darwinian-evolution] Biological structuralism objects to an exclusively Darwinian explanation of natural selection, arguing that other mechanisms also guide evolution, and sometimes implying that these supersede selection altogether.
[src:biological-process/alternatives-to-darwinian-evolution] Structuralists have proposed different mechanisms that might have guided the formation of body plans.
[src:biological-process/alternatives-to-darwinian-evolution] Before Darwin, Étienne Geoffroy Saint-Hilaire argued that animals shared homologous parts, and that if one was enlarged, the others would be reduced in compensation.
[src:biological-process/alternatives-to-darwinian-evolution] After Darwin, D'Arcy Thompson hinted at vitalism and offered geometric explanations in his classic 1917 book *On Growth and Form*.
[src:biological-process/alternatives-to-darwinian-evolution] Adolf Seilacher suggested mechanical inflation for "pneu" structures in Ediacaran biota fossils such as *Dickinsonia*.
[src:biological-process/alternatives-to-darwinian-evolution] Wagner argued for developmental bias, structural constraints on embryonic development.
[src:biological-process/alternatives-to-darwinian-evolution] Stuart Kauffman favoured self-organisation, the idea that complex structure emerges holistically and spontaneously from the dynamic interaction of all parts of an organism.
[src:biological-process/alternatives-to-darwinian-evolution] Michael Denton argued for laws of form by which Platonic universals or "Types" are self-organised.
[src:biological-process/alternatives-to-darwinian-evolution] Gould and Richard Lewontin proposed biological "spandrels", features created as a byproduct of the adaptation of nearby structures.
[src:biological-process/alternatives-to-darwinian-evolution] Gerd Müller and Stuart Newman argued that the appearance in the fossil record of most of the current phyla in the Cambrian explosion was "pre-Mendelian" evolution caused by plastic responses of morphogenetic systems that were partly organized by physical mechanisms.
[src:biological-process/alternatives-to-darwinian-evolution] Brian Goodwin, described by Wagner as part of "a fringe movement in evolutionary biology", denied that biological complexity can be reduced to natural selection, and argued that pattern formation is driven by morphogenetic fields.
[src:biological-process/alternatives-to-darwinian-evolution] Darwinian biologists have criticised structuralism, emphasising that there is plentiful evidence from deep homology that genes have been involved in shaping organisms throughout evolutionary history.
[src:biological-process/alternatives-to-darwinian-evolution] They accept that some structures such as the cell membrane self-assemble, but question the ability of self-organisation to drive large-scale evolution.
[src:biological-process/alternatives-to-darwinian-evolution] Saltationism held that new species arise as a result of large mutations.
[src:biological-process/alternatives-to-darwinian-evolution] It was seen as a much faster alternative to the Darwinian concept of a gradual process of small random variations being acted on by natural selection.
[src:biological-process/alternatives-to-darwinian-evolution] It was popular with early geneticists such as Hugo de Vries, who along with Carl Correns helped rediscover Gregor Mendel's laws of inheritance in 1900, William Bateson, a British zoologist who switched to genetics, and early in his career, Thomas Hunt Morgan.
[src:biological-process/alternatives-to-darwinian-evolution] These ideas developed into mutationism, the mutation theory of evolution.
[src:biological-process/alternatives-to-darwinian-evolution] This held that species went through periods of rapid mutation, possibly as a result of environmental stress, that could produce multiple mutations, and in some cases completely new species, in a single generation, based on de Vries's experiments with the evening primrose, *Oenothera*, from 1886.
[src:biological-process/alternatives-to-darwinian-evolution] The primroses seemed to be constantly producing new varieties with striking variations in form and color, some of which appeared to be new species because plants of the new generation could only be crossed with one another, not with their parents.
[src:biological-process/alternatives-to-darwinian-evolution] However, Hermann Joseph Muller showed in 1918 that the new varieties de Vries had observed were the result of polyploid hybrids rather than rapid genetic mutation.
[src:biological-process/alternatives-to-darwinian-evolution] Initially, de Vries and Morgan believed that mutations were so large as to create new forms such as subspecies or even species instantly.
[src:biological-process/alternatives-to-darwinian-evolution] Morgan's 1910 fruit fly experiments, in which he isolated mutations for characteristics such as white eyes, changed his mind.
[src:biological-process/alternatives-to-darwinian-evolution] He saw that mutations represented small Mendelian characteristics that would only spread through a population when they were beneficial, helped by natural selection.
[src:biological-process/alternatives-to-darwinian-evolution] This represented the germ of the modern synthesis, and the beginning of the end for mutationism as an evolutionary force.
[src:biological-process/alternatives-to-darwinian-evolution] Contemporary biologists accept that mutation and selection both play roles in evolution; the mainstream view is that while mutation supplies material for selection in the form of variation, all non-random outcomes are caused by natural selection.
[src:biological-process/alternatives-to-darwinian-evolution] Masatoshi Nei argues instead that the production of more efficient genotypes by mutation is fundamental for evolution, and that evolution is often mutation-limited.
[src:biological-process/alternatives-to-darwinian-evolution] The endosymbiotic theory implies rare but major events of saltational evolution by symbiogenesis.
[src:biological-process/alternatives-to-darwinian-evolution] Carl Woese and colleagues suggested that the absence of RNA signature continuum between domains of bacteria, archaea, and eukarya shows that these major lineages materialized via large saltations in cellular organization.
[src:biological-process/alternatives-to-darwinian-evolution] Saltation at a variety of scales is agreed to be possible by mechanisms including polyploidy, which certainly can create new species of plant, gene duplication, lateral gene transfer, and transposable elements (jumping genes).
[src:biological-process/alternatives-to-darwinian-evolution] The neutral theory of molecular evolution, proposed by Motoo Kimura in 1968, holds that at the molecular level most evolutionary changes and most of the variation within and between species is not caused by natural selection but by genetic drift of mutant alleles that are neutral.
[src:biological-process/alternatives-to-darwinian-evolution] A neutral mutation is one that does not affect an organism's ability to survive and reproduce.
[src:biological-process/alternatives-to-darwinian-evolution] The neutral theory allows for the possibility that most mutations are deleterious, but holds that because these are rapidly purged by natural selection, they do not make significant contributions to variation within and between species at the molecular level.
[src:biological-process/alternatives-to-darwinian-evolution] Mutations that are not deleterious are assumed to be mostly neutral rather than beneficial.
[src:biological-process/alternatives-to-darwinian-evolution] The theory was controversial as it sounded like a challenge to Darwinian evolution; controversy was intensified by a 1969 paper by Jack Lester King and Thomas H.
[src:biological-process/alternatives-to-darwinian-evolution] Jukes, provocatively but misleadingly titled "Non-Darwinian Evolution".
[src:biological-process/alternatives-to-darwinian-evolution] It provided a wide variety of evidence including protein sequence comparisons, studies of the Treffers mutator gene in *E. coli*, analysis of the genetic code, and comparative immunology, to argue that most protein evolution is due to neutral mutations and genetic drift.
[src:biological-process/alternatives-to-darwinian-evolution] According to Kimura, the theory applies only for evolution at the molecular level, while phenotypic evolution is controlled by natural selection, so the neutral theory does not constitute a true alternative.
[src:biological-process/alternatives-to-darwinian-evolution] The various alternatives to Darwinian evolution by natural selection were not necessarily mutually exclusive.
[src:biological-process/alternatives-to-darwinian-evolution] The evolutionary philosophy of the American palaeontologist Edward Drinker Cope is a case in point.
[src:biological-process/alternatives-to-darwinian-evolution] Cope, a religious man, began his career denying the possibility of evolution.
[src:biological-process/alternatives-to-darwinian-evolution] In the 1860s, he accepted that evolution could occur, but, influenced by Agassiz, rejected natural selection.
[src:biological-process/alternatives-to-darwinian-evolution] Cope accepted instead the theory of recapitulation of evolutionary history during the growth of the embryo - that ontogeny recapitulates phylogeny, which Agassiz believed showed a divine plan leading straight up to man, in a pattern revealed both in embryology and palaeontology.
[src:biological-process/alternatives-to-darwinian-evolution] Cope did not go so far, seeing that evolution created a branching tree of forms, as Darwin had suggested.
[src:biological-process/alternatives-to-darwinian-evolution] Each evolutionary step was however non-random: the direction was determined in advance and had a regular pattern (orthogenesis), and steps were not adaptive but part of a divine plan (theistic evolution).
[src:biological-process/alternatives-to-darwinian-evolution] This left unanswered the question of why each step should occur, and Cope switched his theory to accommodate functional adaptation for each change.
[src:biological-process/alternatives-to-darwinian-evolution] Still rejecting natural selection as the cause of adaptation, Cope turned to Lamarckism to provide the force guiding evolution.
[src:biological-process/alternatives-to-darwinian-evolution] Finally, Cope supposed that Lamarckian use and disuse operated by causing a vitalist growth-force substance, "bathmism", to be concentrated in the areas of the body being most intensively used; in turn, it made these areas develop at the expense of the rest.
[src:biological-process/alternatives-to-darwinian-evolution] Cope's complex set of beliefs thus assembled five evolutionary philosophies: recapitulationism, orthogenesis, theistic evolution, Lamarckism, and vitalism.
[src:biological-process/alternatives-to-darwinian-evolution] Other palaeontologists and field naturalists continued to hold beliefs combining orthogenesis and Lamarckism until the modern synthesis in the 1930s.
[src:biological-process/alternatives-to-darwinian-evolution] By the start of the 20th century, during the eclipse of Darwinism, biologists were doubtful of natural selection, but equally were quick to discount theories such as orthogenesis, vitalism and Lamarckism which offered no mechanism for evolution.
[src:biological-process/alternatives-to-darwinian-evolution] Biology has become Darwinian, but belief in some form of progress (orthogenesis) remains both in the public mind and among biologists.
[src:biological-process/alternatives-to-darwinian-evolution] Ruse argues that evolutionary biologists will probably continue to believe in progress for three reasons.
[src:biological-process/alternatives-to-darwinian-evolution] Firstly, the anthropic principle demands people able to ask about the process that led to their own existence, as if they were the pinnacle of such progress.
[src:biological-process/alternatives-to-darwinian-evolution] Secondly, scientists in general and evolutionists in particular believe that their work is leading them progressively closer to a true grasp of reality, as knowledge increases, and hence (runs the argument) there is progress in nature also.
[src:biological-process/alternatives-to-darwinian-evolution] Ruse notes in this regard that Richard Dawkins explicitly compares cultural progress with memes to biological progress with genes.
[src:biological-process/alternatives-to-darwinian-evolution] Thirdly, evolutionists are self-selected; they are people, such as the entomologist and sociobiologist E.
[src:biological-process/alternatives-to-darwinian-evolution] Wilson, who are interested in progress to supply a meaning for life.
[src:biological-process/altruism-biology] In biology, **altruism** is behaviour by an individual that increases the fitness of another individual while decreasing their own.
[src:biological-process/altruism-biology] Altruism in this sense differs from the philosophical concept of altruism, in which an action would only be called "altruistic" if it was done with the conscious intention of helping another.
[src:biological-process/altruism-biology] In the behavioural sense, there is no such requirement.
[src:biological-process/altruism-biology] As such, it is not evaluated in moral terms; it is the consequences of an action for reproductive fitness that determine whether the action is considered altruistic, not the intentions, if any, with which the action is performed.
[src:biological-process/altruism-biology] The term *altruism* was coined by the French philosopher Auguste Comte in French, as *altruisme*, for an antonym of egoism.
[src:biological-process/altruism-biology] He derived it from the Italian *altrui*, which in turn was derived from Latin *alteri*, meaning "other people" or "somebody else".
[src:biological-process/altruism-biology] Altruistic behaviours appear most obviously in kin relationships, such as in parenting, but may also be evident among wider social groups, such as in social insects.
[src:biological-process/altruism-biology] They allow an individual to increase the success of its genes by helping relatives that share those genes.
[src:biological-process/altruism-biology] Obligate altruism is the permanent loss of direct fitness (with potential for indirect fitness gain).
[src:biological-process/altruism-biology] For example, honey bee workers may forage for the colony.
[src:biological-process/altruism-biology] Facultative altruism is temporary loss of direct fitness (with potential for indirect fitness gain followed by personal reproduction).
[src:biological-process/altruism-biology] For example, a Florida scrub jay may help at the nest, then gain parental territory.
[src:biological-process/altruism-biology] In ethology (the study of behavior), and more generally in the study of social evolution, on occasion, some animals do behave in ways that reduce their individual fitness but increase the fitness of other individuals in the population; this is a functional definition of altruism.
[src:biological-process/altruism-biology] Research in evolutionary theory has been applied to social behaviour, including altruism.
[src:biological-process/altruism-biology] Cases of animals helping individuals to whom they are closely related can be explained by kin selection, and are not considered true altruism.
[src:biological-process/altruism-biology] Beyond the physical exertions that in some species mothers and in some species fathers undertake to protect their young, extreme examples of sacrifice may occur.
[src:biological-process/altruism-biology] One example is matriphagy (the consumption of the mother by her offspring) in the spider *Stegodyphus*; another example is a male spider allowing a female fertilized by him to eat him.
[src:biological-process/altruism-biology] Hamilton's rule describes the benefit of such altruism in terms of Wright's coefficient of relationship to the beneficiary and the benefit granted to the beneficiary minus the cost to the sacrificer.
[src:biological-process/altruism-biology] Should this sum be greater than zero a fitness gain will result from the sacrifice.
[src:biological-process/altruism-biology] When apparent altruism is not between kin, it may be based on reciprocity.
[src:biological-process/altruism-biology] A monkey will present its back to another monkey, who will pick out parasites; after a time the roles will be reversed.
[src:biological-process/altruism-biology] Such reciprocity will pay off, in evolutionary terms, as long as the costs of helping are less than the benefits of being helped and as long as animals will not gain in the long run by "cheating"—that is to say, by receiving favours without returning them.
[src:biological-process/altruism-biology] This is elaborated on in evolutionary game theory and specifically the prisoner's dilemma as social theory.
[src:biological-process/altruism-biology] The existence of altruism in nature is at first sight puzzling, because altruistic behaviour reduces the likelihood that an individual will reproduce.
[src:biological-process/altruism-biology] The idea that *group selection* might explain the evolution of altruism was first broached by Darwin himself in The Descent of Man, and Selection in Relation to Sex, (1871).
[src:biological-process/altruism-biology] The concept of group selection has had a chequered and controversial history in evolutionary biology but the uncritical 'good of the species' tradition came to an abrupt halt in the 1960s, due largely to the work of George C.
[src:biological-process/altruism-biology] Williams, and John Maynard Smith as well as Richard Dawkins.
[src:biological-process/altruism-biology] These evolutionary theorists pointed out that natural selection acts on the individual, and that it is the individual's fitness (number of offspring and grand-offspring produced compared to the rest of the population) that drives evolution.
[src:biological-process/altruism-biology] If the selfishness is hereditary, this will ultimately result in the population consisting entirely of selfish individuals.
[src:biological-process/altruism-biology] However, in the 1960s and 1970s an alternative to the "group selection" theory emerged.
[src:biological-process/altruism-biology] This was the kin selection theory, due originally to W.
[src:biological-process/altruism-biology] Kin selection is an instance of inclusive fitness, which is based on the notion that an individual shares only half its genes with each offspring, but also with each full sibling (See footnote).
[src:biological-process/altruism-biology] From an evolutionary genetic point of view it is therefore as advantageous to help with the upbringing of full siblings as it is to produce and raise one's own offspring.
[src:biological-process/altruism-biology] The two activities are evolutionarily entirely equivalent.
[src:biological-process/altruism-biology] Co-operative breeding (i.e. helping one's parents raise siblings—provided they are full sibs) could thus evolve without the need for group-level selection.
[src:biological-process/altruism-biology] This quickly gained prominence among biologists interested in the evolution of social behaviour.
[src:biological-process/altruism-biology] In 1971 Robert Trivers introduced his reciprocal altruism theory to explain the evolution of helping at the nest of an unrelated breeding pair of birds.
[src:biological-process/altruism-biology] He argued that an individual might act as a helper if there was a high probabilistic expectation of being helped by the recipients at some later date.
[src:biological-process/altruism-biology] If, however, the recipients did not reciprocate when it was possible to do so, the altruistic interaction with these recipients would be permanently terminated.
[src:biological-process/altruism-biology] But if the recipients did not cheat then the reciprocal altruism would continue indefinitely to both parties' advantage.
[src:biological-process/altruism-biology] West-Eberhard and Dawkins) to be evolutionarily unstable because it is prone to invasion by cheats for the same reason that cooperative hunting can be invaded and replaced by cheats.
[src:biological-process/altruism-biology] However, Trivers did make reference to the prisoner's dilemma game which, 10 years later, would restore interest in Trivers' reciprocal altruism theory, but under the title of "tit-for-tat".
[src:biological-process/altruism-biology] In its original form the Prisoner's Dilemma Game (PDG) described two awaiting trial prisoners, A and B, each faced with the choice of betraying the other or remaining silent.
[src:biological-process/altruism-biology] Clearly (d) ("cooperation") is the best mutual strategy, but from the point of view of the individual betrayal is unbeatable (resulting in being set free, or getting only a two-year sentence).
[src:biological-process/altruism-biology] Remaining silent results in a four-year or six-month sentence.
[src:biological-process/altruism-biology] This is exemplified by a further example of the PDG: two strangers attend a restaurant together and decide to split the bill.
[src:biological-process/altruism-biology] The mutually best ploy would be for both parties to order the cheapest items on the menu (mutual cooperation).
[src:biological-process/altruism-biology] But if one member of the party exploits the situation by ordering the most expensive items, then it is best for the other member to do likewise.
[src:biological-process/altruism-biology] In fact, if the fellow diner's personality is completely unknown, and the two diners are unlikely ever to meet again, it is always in one's own best interests to eat as expensively as possible.
[src:biological-process/altruism-biology] Situations in nature that are subject to the same dynamics (rewards and penalties) as the PDG define cooperative behaviour: it is never in the individual's fitness interests to cooperate, even though mutual cooperation rewards the two contestants (together) more highly than any other strategy.
[src:biological-process/altruism-biology] Cooperation cannot evolve under these circumstances.
[src:biological-process/altruism-biology] However, in 1981 Axelrod and Hamilton noted that if the same contestants in the PDG meet repeatedly (the so-called Iterated Prisoner's Dilemma game, IPD) then tit-for-tat (foreshadowed by Robert Triver's reciprocal altruism theory) is a robust strategy which promotes altruism.
[src:biological-process/altruism-biology] In "tit-for-tat" both players' opening moves are cooperation.
[src:biological-process/altruism-biology] Thereafter each contestant repeats the other player's last move, resulting in a seemingly endless sequence of mutually cooperative moves.
[src:biological-process/altruism-biology] However, mistakes severely undermine tit-for-tat's effectiveness, giving rise to prolonged sequences of betrayal, which can only be rectified by another mistake.
[src:biological-process/altruism-biology] The result is that none is evolutionarily stable, and any prolonged series of the iterated prisoner's dilemma game, in which alternative strategies arise at random, gives rise to a chaotic sequence of strategy changes that never ends.
[src:biological-process/altruism-biology] A male peacock with its beautiful but clumsy, aerodynamically unsound tail—a handicap, comparable to a race horse's handicap.
[src:biological-process/altruism-biology] In the light of the Iterated Prisoner's Dilemma Game failing to provide a full answer to the evolution of cooperation or altruism, several alternative explanations have been proposed.
[src:biological-process/altruism-biology] There are striking parallels between altruistic acts and exaggerated sexual ornaments displayed by some animals, particularly certain bird species, such as, amongst others, the peacock.
[src:biological-process/altruism-biology] Both are costly in fitness terms, and both are generally conspicuous to other members of the population or species.
[src:biological-process/altruism-biology] This led Amotz Zahavi to suggest that both might be fitness signals rendered evolutionarily stable by his handicap principle.
[src:biological-process/altruism-biology] If a signal is to remain reliable, and generally resistant to falsification, the signal has to be evolutionarily costly.
[src:biological-process/altruism-biology] Thus, if a (low fitness) liar were to use the highly costly signal, which seriously eroded its real fitness, it would find it difficult to maintain a semblance of normality.
[src:biological-process/altruism-biology] Zahavi borrowed the term "handicap principle" from sports handicapping systems.
[src:biological-process/altruism-biology] These systems are aimed at reducing disparities in performance, thereby making the outcome of contests less predictable.
[src:biological-process/altruism-biology] In a horse handicap race, provenly faster horses are given heavier weights to carry under their saddles than inherently slower horses.
[src:biological-process/altruism-biology] Similarly, in amateur golf, better golfers have fewer strokes subtracted from their raw scores than the less talented players.
[src:biological-process/altruism-biology] The handicap therefore correlates with unhandicapped performance, making it possible, if one knows nothing about the horses, to predict which unhandicapped horse would win an open race.
[src:biological-process/altruism-biology] It would be the one handicapped with the greatest weight in the saddle.
[src:biological-process/altruism-biology] The handicaps in nature are highly visible, and therefore a peahen, for instance, would be able to deduce the health of a potential mate by comparing its handicap (the size of the peacock's tail) with those of the other males.
[src:biological-process/altruism-biology] The loss of the male's fitness caused by the handicap is offset by its increased access to females, which is as much of a fitness concern as is its health.
[src:biological-process/altruism-biology] An altruistic act is, by definition, similarly costly.
[src:biological-process/altruism-biology] It would therefore also signal fitness, and is probably as attractive to females as a physical handicap.
[src:biological-process/altruism-biology] If this is the case altruism is evolutionarily stabilized by sexual selection.
[src:biological-process/altruism-biology] There is an alternate strategy for identifying fit mates which does not rely on one gender having exaggerated sexual ornaments or other handicaps, but is generally applicable to most, if not all sexual creatures.
[src:biological-process/altruism-biology] It derives from the concept that the change in appearance and functionality caused by a non-silent mutation will generally stand out in a population.
[src:biological-process/altruism-biology] This is because that altered appearance and functionality will be unusual, peculiar, and different from the norm within that population.
[src:biological-process/altruism-biology] The norm against which these unusual features are judged is made up of fit attributes that have attained their plurality through natural selection, while less adaptive attributes will be in the minority or frankly rare.
[src:biological-process/altruism-biology] Since the overwhelming majority of mutant features are maladaptive, and it is impossible to predict evolution's future direction, sexual creatures would be expected to prefer mates with the fewest unusual or minority features.
[src:biological-process/altruism-biology] Once a population has become as homogeneous in appearance as is typical of most species, its entire repertoire of behaviours will also be rendered evolutionarily stable, including any altruistic, cooperative and social characteristics.
[src:biological-process/altruism-biology] Thus, in the example of the selfish individual who hangs back from the rest of the hunting pack, but who nevertheless joins in the spoils, that individual will be recognized as being different from the norm, and will therefore find it difficult to attract a mate.
[src:biological-process/altruism-biology] Its genes will therefore have only a very small probability of being passed on to the next generation, thus evolutionarily stabilizing cooperation and social interactions at whatever level of complexity is the norm in that population.
[src:biological-process/altruism-biology] Altruism in animals describes a range of behaviors performed by animals that may be to their own disadvantage but which benefit others.
[src:biological-process/altruism-biology] The costs and benefits are measured in terms of reproductive fitness, or expected number of offspring.
[src:biological-process/altruism-biology] So by behaving altruistically, an organism reduces the number of offspring it is likely to produce itself, but boosts the likelihood that other organisms are to produce offspring.
[src:biological-process/altruism-biology] There are other forms of altruism in nature other than risk-taking behavior, such as reciprocal altruism.
[src:biological-process/altruism-biology] This biological notion of altruism is not identical to the everyday human concept.
[src:biological-process/altruism-biology] For humans, an action would only be called 'altruistic' if it was performed with the conscious intention of helping another.
[src:biological-process/altruism-biology] Yet in the biological sense there is no such requirement.
[src:biological-process/altruism-biology] Instead, until we can communicate directly with other species, an accurate theory to describe altruistic acts between species is Biological Market Theory.
[src:biological-process/altruism-biology] Humans and other animals exchange benefits in several ways, known technically as reciprocity mechanism.
[src:biological-process/altruism-biology] No matter what the mechanism, the common thread is that benefits find their way back to the original giver.
[src:biological-process/altruism-biology] Also known as the "buddy-system", mutual affection between two parties prompts similar behavior in both directions without need to track of daily give-and-take, so long as the overall relationship remains satisfactory.
[src:biological-process/altruism-biology] This is one of the most common mechanisms of reciprocity in nature, this kind is present in humans, primates, and many other mammals.
[src:biological-process/altruism-biology] Also known as, "If you're nice, I'll be nice too." This mechanism of reciprocity is similar to the heuristic of the golden rule, "Treat others how you would like to be treated." Parties mirror one another's attitudes, exchanging favors on the spot.
[src:biological-process/altruism-biology] Instant attitudinal reciprocity occurs among monkeys, and people often rely on it with strangers and acquaintances.
[src:biological-process/altruism-biology] Also known as, "what have you done for me lately?" Individuals keep track of the benefits they exchange with particular partners, which helps them decide to whom to return favors.
[src:biological-process/altruism-biology] This mechanism is typical of chimpanzees and very common among human relationships.
[src:biological-process/altruism-biology] Yet some opposing experimental research suggests that calculated or contingent reciprocity does not spontaneously arise in laboratory experimental settings, despite patterns of behavior.
[src:biological-process/altruism-biology] Biological market theory is an extension of the idea of reciprocal altruism, as a mechanism to explain altruistic acts between unrelated individuals in a more flexible system of exchanging commodities.
[src:biological-process/altruism-biology] The term 'biological market' was first used by Ronald Noe and Hammerstein in 1994 to refer to all the interactions between organisms in which different organisms function as 'traders' that exchange goods and services such as food and water, grooming, warning calls, shelter, etc.
[src:biological-process/altruism-biology] Biological market theory consists of five formal characteristics which present a basis for altruism.
[src:biological-process/altruism-biology] Trading partners are chosen from a number of potential partners.
[src:biological-process/altruism-biology] There is competition among the members of the chosen class to be the most attractive partner.
[src:biological-process/altruism-biology] This competition by 'outbidding' causes an increase in the value of the commodity offered.
[src:biological-process/altruism-biology] Supply and demand determine the bartering value of commodities exchanged.
[src:biological-process/altruism-biology] As in commercial advertisements there is a potential for false information.
[src:biological-process/altruism-biology] The applicability of biological market theory with its emphasis on partner choice is evident in the interactions between the cleaner wrasse and its "client" reef fish.
[src:biological-process/altruism-biology] Cleaners have small territories, which the majority of reef fish species actively visit to invite inspection of their surface, gills, and mouth.
[src:biological-process/altruism-biology] Clients benefit from the removal of parasites while cleaners benefit from the access to a food source.
[src:biological-process/altruism-biology] Some particularly choosy client species have large home ranges that cover several cleaning stations, whereas other clients have small ranges and have access to one cleaning station only (resident clients).
[src:biological-process/altruism-biology] Field observations, field manipulations, and laboratory experiments revealed that whether or not a client has choice options influences several aspects of both cleaner and client behaviour.
[src:biological-process/altruism-biology] Cleaners give choosy clients priority of access.
[src:biological-process/altruism-biology] Choosy clients switch partners if cheated by a cleaner by taking a bite of out of the cleaner, whereas resident clients punish cheats.
[src:biological-process/altruism-biology] Cleaners and resident clients, but not choosy clients, build up relationships before normal cleaning interactions take place.
[src:biological-process/altruism-biology] Cleaners are particularly cooperative if choosy clients are bystanders of an interaction but less so when resident clients are bystanders.
[src:biological-process/altruism-biology] Researchers tested whether wild white-handed gibbon males from Khao Yai National Park, Thailand, increased their grooming activity when the female partner was fertile.
[src:biological-process/altruism-biology] Adult females and males of our study population are codominant (in terms of aggression), they live in pairs or small multi male groups and mate promiscuously.
[src:biological-process/altruism-biology] They found that males groomed females more than vice versa and more grooming was exchanged when females were cycling than during pregnancy or lactation.
[src:biological-process/altruism-biology] The number of copulations/day was elevated when females were cycling, and females copulated more frequently with males on days when they received more grooming.
[src:biological-process/altruism-biology] When males increased their grooming efforts, females also increased their grooming of males, perhaps to equalize give and take.
[src:biological-process/altruism-biology] Although grooming might be reciprocated because of intrinsic benefits of receiving grooming, males also interchange grooming as a commodity for sexual opportunities during a female's fertile period.
[src:biological-process/altruism-biology] An example of altruism is found in the cellular slime moulds, such as *Dictyostelium mucoroides*.
[src:biological-process/altruism-biology] These protists live as individual amoebae until starved, at which point they aggregate and form a multicellular fruiting body in which some cells sacrifice themselves to promote the survival of other cells in the fruiting body.
[src:biological-process/altruism-biology] When it comes to altruism in kin/non-kin recognition, few studies have focused on this trait in crops.
[src:biological-process/altruism-biology] Despite most crops growing in monocultures, there is evidence that they are able to recognize kin and other cultivars.
[src:biological-process/altruism-biology] For example, cultivated soybean plants were able to recognize a distant ancestor and unrelated neighbors.
[src:biological-process/altruism-biology] In that experiment, plants were grown in combinations of relation to each other (same cultivar or different cultivar) in pots and their biomass of stems, leaves, and roots were measured to see how the plants responded growing next to kin or non-kin.
[src:biological-process/altruism-biology] Crops, unlike wild plants, are highly cultivated.
[src:biological-process/altruism-biology] The evolution of traits such as altruism can thus be bred into them through the selection of the trait.
[src:biological-process/altruism-biology] In agriculture, the importance of yield is stressed, therefore breeding crop cultivars to favor altruism can decrease competitiveness and increase yield.
[src:biological-process/altruism-biology] It has been shown that using mass selection early in the breeding process selects against altruism in an individual, but using mixed individual and group selection favors altruism.
[src:biological-process/anabolism] Polymerization, an anabolic pathway used to build macromolecules such as nucleic acids, proteins, and polysaccharides, uses condensation reactions to join monomers.
[src:biological-process/anabolism] Macromolecules are created from smaller molecules using enzymes and cofactors.
[src:biological-process/anabolism] Anabolism is powered by catabolism, where large molecules are broken down into smaller parts and then used up in cellular respiration.
[src:biological-process/anabolism] Many anabolic processes are powered by the cleavage of adenosine triphosphate (ATP).
[src:biological-process/anabolism] Anabolism usually involves reduction and decreases entropy, making it unfavorable without energy input.
[src:biological-process/anabolism] The starting materials, called the precursor molecules, are joined using the chemical energy made available from hydrolyzing ATP, reducing the cofactors NAD+, NADP+, and FAD, or performing other favorable side reactions.
[src:biological-process/anabolism] Occasionally it can also be driven by entropy without energy input, in cases like the formation of the phospholipid bilayer of a cell, where hydrophobic interactions aggregate the molecules.
[src:biological-process/anabolism] The reducing agents NADH, NADPH, and FADH2, as well as metal ions, act as cofactors at various steps in anabolic pathways.
[src:biological-process/anabolism] NADH, NADPH, and FADH2 act as electron carriers, while charged metal ions within enzymes stabilize charged functional groups on substrates.
[src:biological-process/anabolism] Substrates for anabolism are mostly intermediates taken from catabolic pathways during periods of high energy charge in the cell.
[src:biological-process/anabolism] Anabolic processes build organs and tissues.
[src:biological-process/anabolism] These processes produce growth and differentiation of cells and increase in body size, a process that involves synthesis of complex molecules.
[src:biological-process/anabolism] Examples of anabolic processes include the growth and mineralization of bone and increases in muscle mass.
[src:biological-process/anabolism] Endocrinologists have traditionally classified hormones as anabolic or catabolic, depending on which part of metabolism they stimulate.
[src:biological-process/anabolism] The classic anabolic hormones are the anabolic steroids, which stimulate protein synthesis and muscle growth, and especially insulin, which is the main anabolic hormone of the body, regulating the metabolism of protein, carbohydrates, and fats.
[src:biological-process/anabolism] Photosynthetic carbohydrate synthesis in plants and certain bacteria is an anabolic process that produces glucose, cellulose, starch, lipids, and proteins from CO2.
[src:biological-process/anabolism] It uses the energy produced from the light-driven reactions of photosynthesis, and creates the precursors to these large molecules via carbon assimilation in the photosynthetic carbon reduction cycle, a.k.a. the Calvin cycle.
[src:biological-process/anabolism] All amino acids are formed from intermediates in the catabolic processes of glycolysis, the citric acid cycle, or the pentose phosphate pathway.
[src:biological-process/anabolism] From the citric acid cycle, α-ketoglutarate is converted into glutamate and subsequently glutamine, proline, and arginine; and oxaloacetate is converted into aspartate and subsequently asparagine, methionine, threonine, and lysine.
[src:biological-process/anabolism] During periods of high blood sugar, glucose 6-phosphate from glycolysis is diverted to the glycogen-storing pathway.
[src:biological-process/anabolism] It is changed to glucose-1-phosphate by phosphoglucomutase and then to UDP-glucose by UTP--glucose-1-phosphate uridylyltransferase.
[src:biological-process/anabolism] Glycogen synthase adds this UDP-glucose to a glycogen chain.
[src:biological-process/anabolism] Glucagon is traditionally a catabolic hormone, but also stimulates the anabolic process of gluconeogenesis by the liver, and to a lesser extent the kidney cortex and intestines, during starvation to prevent low blood sugar.
[src:biological-process/anabolism] It is the process of converting pyruvate into glucose.
[src:biological-process/anabolism] Pyruvate can come from the breakdown of glucose, lactate, amino acids, or glycerol.
[src:biological-process/anabolism] The gluconeogenesis pathway has many reversible enzymatic processes in common with glycolysis, but it is not the process of glycolysis in reverse.
[src:biological-process/anabolism] It uses different irreversible enzymes to ensure the overall pathway runs in one direction only.
[src:biological-process/anabolism] Anabolism operates with separate enzymes from catalysis, which undergo irreversible steps at some point in their pathways.
[src:biological-process/anabolism] This allows the cell to regulate the rate of production and prevent an infinite loop, also known as a futile cycle, from forming with catabolism.
[src:biological-process/anabolism] The balance between anabolism and catabolism is sensitive to ADP and ATP, otherwise known as the energy charge of the cell.
[src:biological-process/anabolism] High amounts of ATP cause cells to favor the anabolic pathway and slow catabolic activity, while excess ADP slows anabolism and favors catabolism.
[src:biological-process/anabolism] These pathways are also regulated by circadian rhythms, with processes such as glycolysis fluctuating to match an animal's normal periods of activity throughout the day.
[src:biological-process/anabolism] The word *anabolism* is from Neo-Latin, with roots from Ancient Greek: ἀνά, "upward" and βάλλειν, "to throw".
[src:biological-process/biological-process] A **biological process** is a processes necessary for an organism to live, and therefore shapes its capacity to interact with its environment.
[src:biological-process/biological-process] Biological processes are made of many chemical reactions or other events that are involved in the persistence and transformation of life forms.
[src:biological-process/biological-process] Regulation of biological processes occurs when any process is modulated in its frequency, rate or extent.
[src:biological-process/biological-process] Biological processes are regulated by many means; examples include the control of gene expression, protein modification or interaction with a protein or substrate molecule.
